Hello World

examples

Hello World - Basic

File Name:
main.rs
File Contents:
fn main() { println!("Hello world!"); }
Compile:
rustc main.rs
Run:
main
Examples

Hello World - Input Name

File Name:
hello.rs
use std::io::stdin; fn main() { let mut name = String::new(); println!("name: "); if let Err(error) = stdin().read_line(&mut name) { println!("Error: {}", error); return; } name.pop(); // Remove the newline character. println!("Hello, {}!", name); }
Run:
rustc hello.rs ./hello

Hello World - Name from Command Line Arguments

File Name:
hello.rs
use std::env::args; fn main() { let args: Vec<String> = args().collect(); if args.len() < 2 { println!("Usage: {} NAME", args[0]); return; } let name = &args[1..].join(" ");; println!("Hello, {}!", name); }
Run:
rustc hello.rs ./hello your_name_here

Language Fundamentals

language-fundamentals-only, fundamentals-only

Created / 1st Release

Created2006
1st ReleaseMay 2015

Created By

Graydon Hoare creator

Comments

// This is a comment.
Start a comment with '//'. //

Comments - Inline

/* inline comment */
A comment embedded in a statement. Example
let a /* Type determined by inferencing */ = 42.
/*, */, /**/

Comments - Multiline

/* Multiline Comment */
Start a multiline comment with '/*'. End with '*/>' /*, */, /**/, block

Doc Comments

/// This is a doc comment.
/// This doc comment /// adds content to the /// following function. fn documented_function() { ... }
Doc comments are placed before the item being commented on. Use a triple forward slash (///) on each line. code, documentation, docstring-only, docstr-only, doc-string-only, doc-str-only ///

Doc Comments - Markdown Format

/// # Heading 1 /// ## Heading 2 /// /// In **bold** or __bold__ /// In *italics* or _italics_ /// In ~~strikethrough~~ /// /// [Link](http//speedsheet.io)
Doc comments support CommonMark Markdown. CommonMark: https://commonmark.org/help/ code, documentation, docstring-only, docstr-only, doc-string-only, doc-str-only ///

Block

{ ... }
A block of code with it's own scope separate from the local scope. Example:
let a = 10; { let a = 5 + a; println!("a = {}", a); } println!("a = {}", a); // Prints: // // a = 15 // a = 10

Block Expression

= { ... return_value }
Defines a block that returns a value. Return a value like any other expression, leave the semicolon (;) off. Example:
let value = { 10_i32.pow(2) }; println!("value = {}", value); // Prints: "value = 100"

Identifiers

( letter | unicode_letter | _ ) ( digit | letter | unicode_letter | _ ) *
[_a-zA-Zunicode][_0-9a-zA-Zunicode]*
Case sensitive. The first character must be an alphabet letter, Unicode letter or underscore. The first character can not be a digit. All other characters can be alphabet letters, Unicode letters, underscores or digits. A single underscore ('_') is not allowed. Examples:
_identifier identifier ì‹ë³„ì item_1
Invalid:
_ 3_items ğŸˆ
rust names, variable names, module names, class names rules, Valid, Name, Correct

Runtime Data Types

Rust does not store data types at runtime. Rust does not need to know the data types at runtime as the compiler has exhaustively checked that everything is correct.

Cargo - Build / Debug

cargo build
Compiles the program. The build includes debugging code and will create a bigger, slower executable vs. the release version. Directory:
project/ â””â”€â”€ target/ â””â”€â”€ debug/

Cargo - Build / Release

cargo build -r
cargo build --release
Compiles the program for release. This strips all debugging code from the executable resulting in a faster, smaller build. Directory:
project/target/release
cargo, compile, create, release, production, executable, -r, --release

Cargo - Run Tests With Output

Runs tests but displays the standard out. The default is not to show anything sent to the standard out unless the test fails. The -- --nocapture needs to be at the end of the command. function, tests, testing, standard out, stdout, print, show, display --nocapture

a - bSubtract

Arithmetic Assignment Operators

a += b Add
a -= bSubtract
a *= bMultiply
a /= bDivide
a %= bModulo / Remainder
Calculate the operation and save the result in a. +=, -=, *=, /= %= add, plus, subtract, minus, multiply, divide, modulo, modulus

Calculate the operation and save the result in a:

a ^= bBitwise XOR

a >>= shift_countBitwise Shift Right

Boolean, !, &&, || and, or, not, negation, bang

Ternary Operator / Inline If

= if expression { true_value } else { false_value }
Full Form:
let value = if expression { true_value } else { false_value };
Evaluates a conditional expression and returns one value if true, and the other if false. Must be terminated with a semicolon (;). Really this is just a regular if else statement but on one line. Example:
let a = 10; let more_or_less = if a > 5 {"more"} else {"less"}; println!("{} is {} than 5.", a, more_or_less); // Prints "10 is more than 5."
Ternary conditional operator, tertiary, expression Inline If, iif, if else ternary-only

Operator / Expression Precedence

From Highest to Lowest:
::Paths
.method()Methods
.fieldFieldsleft to right
function(), array[]Functions, Array Indexes
- * ! & &mutUnary Operators
as :Casting, : Operatorleft to right
* / %Multiplicativeleft to right
+ -Additiveleft to right
<< >>Bitwise Shiftleft to right
&Bitwise ANDleft to right
^Bitwise XORleft to right

== != < <= > >=Comparisonuse parenthesis
&&Logical ANDleft to right
||Logical ORleft to right

return break ||Flow Control, Closures
order of operations

Operator Overloading / Implementing

Implement Equals Operator - Using Derive

#[derive(PartialEq)] struct Type { ... }
To support the == and != operators, use the derive attribute. Example:
#[derive(PartialEq)] struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20 }; let point_2 = Point { x: 20, y: 10 }; println!("Point 1 == 2?: {}", point_1 == point_2); // Prints: Point 1 == 2?: false
==, !=, #derive, #[derive(eq)] #[derive(partialeq)], partialeq, compare, comparator

Implement Equals Operator - Using Trait

impl PartialEq<Type> for Type { fn eq(&self, other: &Type) -> bool { self.... == other.... } }
To support the == and != operators, implement the PartialEq trait. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } impl PartialEq<Point> for Point { fn eq(&self, other: &Point) -> bool { self.x == other.x && self.y == other.y } } impl Eq for Point {} let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20 }; let point_2 = Point { x: 20, y: 10 }; println!("Point 1 == 2?: {}", point_1 == point_2); // Prints: Point 1 == 2?: false
==, !=, partialeq, impl, compare, comparator

Control Structures

statements, flow control-only, control-structure-only, control-structures-only control-statements-only

Control Structures - Basics

If Else
if expression { ... } if expression { ... } else if expression { ... } else { ... }
For
for value in start..end_plus_one { ... } for value in start..=end { ... } for value in iterator { ... }
Loop
loop { ... } loop { ... continue; ... break; ... }
Match
match item { value_1 => { ... } value_2 | value_3 => { ... } min_1..max_plus_one_1 => { ... } bind_value @ min_2..max_plus_one_2 => { ... } _ => { ... } }
While
while expression { ... }
summary

If Else

else, if-only, if-else, if-else-only

If - If Else

if expression { ... }
if expression { ... } else if expression { ... } else { ... }
Example:
let value = 42; if value < 42 { println!("{} is less than 42.", value); } else if value == 42 { println!("{} is 42.", value); } else { println!("{} is greater than 42.", value); }

If - If Let

if let pattern = expression { ... } else { ... }
Uses pattern matching to evaluate an expression. If the expression matches, the true part of the if clause is executed. Use where you need to test for a single value of an enum and instead of using a more verbose match statement. (e.g. where Some() is involved) Uses let's refutability test. Above is Equivalent To:
match expression { pattern => { ... } _ => { ... } }
Example:
let numbers = [Some(1), None, Some(3), None, Some(5)]; for number in numbers { if let Some(value) = number { println!("{}", value); } else { println!("[none]"); } } // Prints: // // 1 // [none] // 3 // [none] // 5
pattern matching if-let-only

For

for-only, fors-only, for-in, for-in-only, loop

For - In Range

for value in start..end_plus_one { ... }
for value in start..=end { ... }
Example: For With .. :
for value in 0..3 { println!("{}", value); } // Prints Values: 0, 1, 2
For With ..= :
for value in 0..=3 { println!("{}", value); } // Prints Values: 0, 1, 2, 3
.., ..=

For - In Collection

for value in collection { ... }
Iterates over each item in the collection using its iterator. Example:
let vec_1 = vec!["one", "two", "three"]; for item in vec_1 { println!("{} ", item); } // Prints: // // one // two // three
foreach, for-each, collection, .iter()

For - In Iterator

for value in iterator { ... }
Iterates over each item in the iterator. Example:
let vec_1 = vec!["one", "two", "three"]; let iterator = vec_1.iter(); for item in iterator { println!("{} ", item); } // Prints: // // one // two // three
iterator, iterate

For - Break, Continue

for ... { ... continue; ... break; ... }

Let

let-only

Let - Let Else

let pattern = expression else { // Handle exception here. return; };
Implements a guard around the pattern if the pattern doesn't match. Results are passed to the surrounding scope. The else block must have a return or other divergent expression. Example:
let some_value = Some(42); let Some(value) = some_value else { println!("No value found"); return; }; println!("value = {}", value); // Prints: value = 42
guard expression, pattern matching let-else-only

Loop

loop-only, loops-only

Loop

loop { ... }
loop { ... continue; ... break; ... }
Loops continuously until break is called. Use to create an infinite loop. Example:
let mut value = 0; loop { value += 1; println!("{}", value); if value > 4 { break; } } // Prints values 1, 2, 3, 4.
break, continue, infinite

Loop - Loop Expression / Return Value

let returned_value = loop { ... break return_value; ... };
Loops and then returns a value on break. Loops continuously until break is called. Requires a semicolon (;) after the block. Example:
let mut value = 0; let result = loop { value += 1; if value > 4 { break value; } }; println!("Result = {}.", result); // Prints: "Result = 5."
break loop-only, expression, with return value

Loop - Named / Nested Loop

'name: loop { ... continue name; ... break name; ... }
Nested:
'outer_name: loop { 'inner_name: loop { ... continue outer_name; ... break outer_name; ... } }
Labels each loop with a name. Allows break and continue statements to operate on an outer loop. break, continue, labeled

Match

match-only, matches-only, pattern matching, =>

Match - Basics

match item { value_1 => { ... }, value_2 | value_3 => { ... }, value_3 if condition => { ... } min_1..max_plus_one_1 => { ... }, bind_value @ min_2..max_plus_one_2 => { ... }, _ => { ... } }
Match Expression:
let value = match item { value_1 => { ... }, value_2 => { ... } };
Match Statement Parts:
match expression { match_arm, match_arm, pattern => code pattern => code pattern if condition => code }

Match - Details

Match - Single Value

match item { value_1 => { ... }, value_2 => { ... }, _ => { ... } }

Match - Multiple Values

match item { value_1 | value_2 => { ... }, value_3 | value_4 => { ... }, ... }
| or

Match - Value If

match item { value if condition => { ... }, ... }
conditional

Match - Value Range

match item { min..max_plus_one => { ... }, min..=max => { ... }, ... }
.., ..=

Match - Bind To Value

match item { bind_value @ min_2..max_plus_one_2 => { ... }, ... }

Match - Match Expression

Match Expression:
let value = match item { value_1 => { ... }, value_2 => { ... }, ... };
Returns a value from a match expression. Example:
let value = 200; let returned_value = match value { 200 => { "OK" }, 400 => { "Bad Request" }, 500 => { "Server Error" }, _ => { "Unknown" } }; println!("Returns {}.", returned_value); // Prints "">
return value

Match - Match Enum

match enum_value { Enum1::Value1 => { ... }, Enum1::Value2 => { ... }, Enum1::Value3 => { ... }, ... };
enums

Match - Match Enum Tuple

match enum_value { Enum1::Value1 (field_1) => { ... }, Enum1::Value2 (field_2) => { ... }, Enum1::Value3 (field_3, field_4) => { ... }, ... };
enums, fields, values, elements

Match - Match Enum Struct

match enum_value { Enum1::Value1 {field_1} => { ... }, Enum1::Value2 {field_2} => { ... }, Enum1::Value3 {field_3, field_4} => { ... }, ... };
enums, fields, values, elements, variant

Match - Match Enum Struct - Ignore Fields

match enum_value { Enum1::Value1 {..} => { ... }, ... };
Use {..} to match only the variant and ignore the fields inside. enums, fields, values, elements, {..}, .., variant

Variables

vars-only, var-only, variable-only, variables-only, assignment

Variables - Basics

Declare Only:
let name: type;
Constant:
const name: type = value;

let name: type = value;
With Type Inferencing:

summary

Variable - Create

create, new, instantiate, set, declare, assign

Variable - Constant - Create

const name: type = value;
Defines a constant, an immutable variable. Constants can be declared globally outside a function. The type must be declared (no type inferencing). The compiler replaces the constant identifier with the actual value at compile time. Example:
const OK_STATUS_CODE: i32 = 200; fn main() { println!("OK Status = {}", OK_STATUS_CODE); }
const, global

Variable - Local - Create

let name: type = value;
let name = value;
Creates an immutable variable. If the type is not included, the inference engine will try to determine it from the use of the variable. Example:
let int_1: i32 = 42;
immutable, let, scope#

Variable - Static - Create

static STATIC_1: type = value;
Creates a global immutable variable. Static data is stored in the compiled binary. Statics can be created inside or outside functions. You must declare the type for a static variable (no type inferencing). Example:
static INT_1: i32 = 42; println!("{}", INT_1); // Prints: "42"
Rust Docs: Static immutable, static, global, scope

Variable - Static - Create With 'static

static STATIC_1: &'static type = &value;
Creates a global immutable variable. 'static indicates the value lives for the entire life of the program. Static data is stored in the compiled binary. Statics can be created inside or outside functions. You must declare the type for a static variable (no type inferencing). Examples:
static INT_1: &'static i32 = &42; println!("{}", INT_1); // Prints: "42"
static STR_1: &'static str = "42"; println!("{}", STR_1); // Prints: "42"
static, 'static immutable, static, global, scope

Variable - Mutable - Create

let mut name: type = value;
Creates a mutable variable. Example:
let mut int_1: i32 = 42; int_1 = int_1 + 10;
let, mut

Variable - Create With Type Inferencing

let name = value;
This will create a variable of type matching the value. Example:
let int_1 = 42; // Assigns int_1 as type i32;
let

Variable - Define Before Use

let name: type;
let mut name: type;
Define a variable before assiging a value. The value must be assigned at some point afterwards. Example:
let value:i32; let flag = true; if flag { value = 1; } else { value = -1; } // Sets value to 1.
predefine

Variable - Cast

Converts a value from one type to another. Casting never happens implicitly. You must always explicitly cast your variables. Example:
let value = 10_i32; value_i8 = value as i8; println!("Value is {}", value_i8)
as type, change, convert, conversions, converting

Returns the variable type as a string. Not guaranteed to give consistent results. Use for testing only. Example:
use std::any::type_name; fn type_of<T>(_: T) -> &'static str { type_name::<T>() } let type_name = type_of(1_i32); println! ("Type = {}", type_name); // Prints "Type = i32"
std::any::type_name, type_name, get, retrieve, type of

Variable Scope

Variable Scope - Basics

Global, Local, Block:
static global_variable:i32 = 1; fn func1() { let local_variable = 2; { let block_variable = 3; } }
Shadowing:
fn func1() { let variable_1 = 1; { // Block, Shadows Outer Variable: let variable_1 = 2; } }
summary

Variable Scope - Shadowing

Shadowing happens when a block variable overshadows a local variable of the same name. The local variable is not accessable while the block variable is in scope. Global (static) variables can NOT be shadowed. Example:
let a = 1; println!("local a = {}", a); { let a = 2; println!("block a = {}", a); } println!("local a = {}", a);

Variables - let vs const vs static

let:
Defines a variable with local scope.
static:
Defines a variable with global scope.
const:
Defines a value. The compiler replace every use of the constant with the actual value at compile time.
versus, scope

Let - Refutability Test

Let runs a refutability test before assigning a value. It checks to see if the new value is (or can be) different to the current value. If is different, then it is refutable. If not, it is irrefutable.
Refutable Returns true
IrrefutableReturns false
refutable, irrefutable

Ownership

ownership-only

Ownership - Rules - Owner

1. Resources have one and only one owner. 2. When the owner goes out of scope, the resource is freed. 3. Ownership is movable (transferable).

Ownership - Rules - Borrow Immutable

1. There is no limit on the number of borrowers. 2. Immutable borrowers prevents any mutable borrows.

Ownership - Rules - Borrow Mutable

1. One and only one mutable borrower at a time. 2. Mutable borrow is not allowed while there are immutable borrowers.

Ownership - Syntax - Borrow Immutable

&owner
By Assignment:
let borrower = &owner;
When Passing:
function_1(&owner);
Borrow (pass) a resource without passing ownership of it. Use ampersand (&) to denote borrowing. There is no limit on the number of borrowers for an immutable resource. Examples:
let owner = Box::new(42_i32); let borrower = &owner; println!("{}", &owner); println!("{}", borrower); // Prints: // // "42" // "42"
&, borrowing

Ownership - Syntax - Borrow Mutable

&mut owner
By Assignment:
let borrower = &mut owner;
When Passing:
function_1(&mut owner);
Borrow (pass) a mutable resource without passing ownership of it. Use ampersand mut (&mut) to denote borrowing. There can only be one mutable borrower at a time for a mutable resource. There can be any number of immutable borrowers, but if there are, no mutable borrowers are allowed. Examples:
let mut owner = Box::new(42_i32); let borrower = &mut owner; println!("{}", borrower); // Prints: // // "42" // "42"
&, mut

Ownership - Moving Ownership

By Assignment:
let new_owner = owner;
When Passing:
function_1(owner);
Passes ownership of the resource to the new variable or to the called function. After a move, owner can not be referenced. Examples: By Assignment:
let owner = Box::new(42_i32); let new_owner = owner; // NO: // println!("{}", owner); // YES: println!("{}", new_owner); // Prints: "42"
By Passing:
fn take_ownership(value: Box<i32>) { println!("{}", value); } let owner = Box::new(42_i32); take_ownership(owner); // Prints: "42" // NO! // println!("{}", owner);
move, take

Pattern Matching

Pattern Matching - Own

Example:
if let Some(value) = option_value_1 { ... }
Takes ownership of the wrapped value. Without either ref or ref mut, the right hand value is moved out of the wrapping item and ownership is moved to the variable on the left of the =.

Pattern Matching - Reference

Example:
if let Some(ref value) = option_value_1 { ... }
Borrows the wrapped value. borrow ref

Pattern Matching - Reference Mutably

Example:
if let Some(value) = option_value_1 { *value = ...; }
Borrows and mutates the wrapped value. mutate, borrow ref mut

Types

Type - Type Aliasing

type Alias1 = Type;
Allows you to create an alias for a type for readability. Example:
type Kilometers = usize; let distance: Kilometers = 42;
define custom type, assign

Type - Type Aliasing With Generics

type Alias1<T> = Type<T>; type Alias1<T> = Type<T, U, V>;
Allows you to create an alias for a type with generics for readability. Example:
type MyResult<T> = Result<T, MyError>;
define custom type, assign

Type - Type Inferencing

Rust determines the variable type by looking ahead to see how it is used. It then creates variable of the correct type. Note: You must use the correct literal types. You can not substitute integers for floats or vice versa. Example: Infer type of value:
// Infers value as i64: fn square(x: i64) -> i64 { x * x } fn main() { // Infer type: let value = 4; // Inference happens here: i64 let square = square(value); println!("{} squared is {}.", value, square); }

Never

The never type or "!" type. This is thrown by the compiler and defines a place in the code that has nowhere to go. Fix by adding a return or reworking the code. Technically it denotes a computation that never completes. !, never-only, !-only

Str

Type:
&str
Defines an immutable string of type str. Features:
  • Is Immutable
  • Stored as an u8 Vector
  • Stores in UTF-8 Format
  • Can NOT be created directly1.
Can be stored in:
  • Stack
  • Heap
  • Compiled Code
1 - Can't be created directly as the compiler can't determine the size at compile time (str does not store it's own length). Rust Docs: std::str strs, str-only, strs-only &strs, &str-only, &strs-only data type, slice, string std::str, ::str

Str - Create

= "A String"
let str_1: &str = "A String";
Type:
&str
Defines an immutable string slice. Technically, it returns a reference to the string slice. This string is stored as part of the actual program, not on the stack or in the heap. Examples:
let str_1 = "abc"; println!("{}", str_1); // Prints: "abc"
Rust Docs: std::str new, instantiate

Str - Substring

first= text.chars().next().unwrap()
last= text.chars().last().unwrap()
left= text.chars().take(length).collect::<String>()
middle= text.chars().skip(start).take(length).collect::<String>()
= text.chars().skip(start).take(end_plus_1 - start).collect::<String>()
right= text.chars().skip(text.chars().count() - length).collect::<String>()
Examples:
text= "12345"// "12345"
first= text.chars().next().unwrap()// "1"
last= text.chars().last().unwrap()// "5"
left= text.chars().take(3).collect::<String>()// "123"
middle= text.chars().skip(1).take(3).collect::<String>()// "234"
= text.chars().skip(1).take(4 - 1).collect::<String>()// "234"
right= text.chars().skip(text.chars().count() - 3).collect::<String>()// "345"
Rust Docs: std::str Partial, Slice, slicing, unicode, chars, .substring()

Str - Split

= str_1.split(split_string)
Usage:

Returns:
Split
Returns an iterator of strings split on the split string. If no split found, returns the original string (1 value). If no value before or after the split, empty strings are returned. The split string is not returned. Example:
let str_1 = "one\ntwo\nthree\n"; let lines: Vec<&str> = str_1.split("\n").collect(); for line in lines.iter() { println!("'{}'", line); } // Prints: // // 'one' // 'two' // 'three' // ''

String - Create With Capacity

= String::with_capacity(size);
Creates an empty string with a capacity of the given size in bytes. Use this if you know what size the string needs to be or you want to avoid reallocating memory as the string grows. Bytes are not equivalent to characters. Characters are UTF8 encoded and may require up to 4 bytes per character. size is type usize. Rust Docs: std::string::String::with_capacity string::with_capacity(), with_capacity()

String - Substring

first= text.chars().next().unwrap()
last= text.chars().last().unwrap()
left= text.chars().take(length).collect::<String>()
middle= text.chars().skip(start).take(length).collect::<String>()
= text.chars().skip(start).take(end_plus_1 - start).collect::<String>()
right= text.chars().skip(text.chars().count() - length).collect::<String>()
Examples:
text= "12345".to_string()// "12345"

last= text.chars().last().unwrap()// "5"
left= text.chars().take(3).collect::<String>()// "123"
middle= text.chars().skip(1).take(3).collect::<String>()// "234"
= text.chars().skip(1).take(4 - 1).collect::<String>()// "234"
right= text.chars().skip(text.chars().count() - 3).take(3).collect::<String>()// "345"
Rust Docs: std::string::String.chars() Rust Docs: std::str::Chars Partial, Slice, slicing, .substring()

String Literal - To String

= "string literal".to_string();
Or:
= String::from("string literal");
Use .to_string() or ::from() to convert a string literal to a string. String literals are stored as type &str and must be explicitly converted to type String. This is because string literals are stored in code whereas strings are stored on the heap. Rust Docs: std::string::String to-string Convert, conversion, converting, from, slice

str vs &str vs String

str:
  • The Actual String Data
  • Immutable u8 Array
  • UTF-8 Encoded
  • On Heap | Stack | Program Binary
  • Not Directly Referenceable
&str:
  • References str Data
  • Borrow Only
  • Knows Length
For:
  • Read Only Strings
  • Accessing String Data
String:
  • Mutable u8 Array
  • UTF-8 Encoded
  • Owns Data
  • On Heap
For:
  • Ownership
  • Passing
  • Dynamic String

Enum

enums, enum-only, enums-only data type

Enum - Basics

enum Enum1 { Value1, Value2, Value3 } let value_1 = Enum1::Value1;
Print:
println!("{}", Enum1::Value1 as u8);
Match:
match value_1 { Enum1:Value1 => ..., Enum1:Value2 => ..., Enum1:Value3 => ... }
Enums With Properties:
enum Enum1 { Value1(i32), Value2(char), Value3(String) Value4{x: i32, y: i32} }
summary

Enum - Create

new, variants

Enum - Define

enum Enum1 { Item1, Item2, Item3 }
= Enum1::Item1
Creates an enum with the defined items. By default enum items are stored as a sequence of integers. Example:
enum Colors { Red, Green, Blue } let red = Color::Red; println!("Red = {}", Color::Red as u8); println!("Green = {}", Color::Green as u8); println!("Blue = {}", Color::Blue as u8); // Red = 0 // Green = 1 // Blue = 2

Enum - Define With Explicit Values

enum Enum1 { Item1 = value_1, Item2 = value_2, Item3 }
= Enum1::Item1
Creates an enum where each item has a custom value. Items with no explicit values will continue in ascending values from the last value set. Example:
enum Color { Red = 10, Green = 20, Blue } println!("Red = {}", Color::Red as u8); println!("Green = {}", Color::Green as u8); println!("Blue = {}", Color::Blue as u8); // Red = 10 // Green = 20 // Blue = 21
internal, stored

Enum - Define As Struct

enum Enum1 { Item1 {field: type}, Item2 {field_1: type, field_2: type}, Item3 {field_1: type, field_2: type, ...} }
= Enum1::Item1{field: value}
Creates an enum where the items have struct values. Example:
enum Shape { Circle {radius: u32}, Rectangle {height: u32, width: u32}, } let circle_1 = Shape::Circle {radius: 5}; let rectangle_1 = Shape::Rectangle {height: 4, width: 6};
internal, stored

Enum - Define As Tuples

enum Enum1 { Item1 (type), Item2 (type, type), Item3 (type, type, ...) }
= Enum1::Item1(value)
Creates an enum with items containing tuple data. Example:
enum Color { Base {u32}, Primary (u32), Secondary (u32) } let base = Color::Base(0xFF0000)
internal, stored

Enum - Operations

Enum - Equals

value == Enum1::Variant1
Usage:
if Enum1::Item1 == value ...
Compares a value to an enum variant. Requires the enum implements the PartialEq trait. Works best with simple enums (no internal values). For complex enums, the internal values are taken into account. Imlement using #[derive(PartialEq)]. Example:
#[derive(PartialEq)] enum Color { Red, Green, Blue } let color = Color::Red; if color == Color::Red { println!("Color Red"); }; // Prints: Color Red
Rust Docs: std::cmp::PartialEq equals, is value, is type, is variant

Enum - Equals using matches!

matches!(value, Enum1::Variant1)
Usage:
if matches!(value, Enum1::Variant1) ...
Compares a value to an enum variant. Example:
enum Color { Red, Green, Blue } let color = Color::Red; if matches!(color, Color::Red) { println!("Color Red"); }; // Prints: Color Red
Rust Docs: std::cmp::PartialEq equals, is value, is type, is variant, matches!(), matches()

Enum - Not Equals

= ! matches!(value1, Enum1::Item1)
or
match value { Enum1::Item1 => {}, _ => ... // Put code here. }
Testss if the enum is NOT a particular variant. not, equals, not value, is not type, match, !matches!(), matcesh!(), matches()

Enum - To Integer

= Enum1.Item1 as u8
Cast enum items to unsigned integer. This only works enums with no data attached to them (no tuple or struct enums). convert, conversion

Enum - Patterns

Enum - Equals / If Let Variant

if let Enum1::Item1 = value ...
or
match value { Enum1::Item1 => ..., _ => ... }
Tests if the enum is a particular variant of it (e.g. is it Item1?). Use match or if let. There is no direct way to check if an enum is a specific variant out of the box. equals, is value, is type, match

Enum - If Let - Borrow Wrapped Value

if let Type::Variant(value) = &value_1 { ...
or
if let Type::Variant(ref value) = value_1 { ...
Borrows the wrapped value inside. ref, as reference, with

Enum - If Let - Mutably Borrow Wrapped Value

if let Type::Variant(ref mut value) = value_1 { ...
} Mutably borrows the wrapped value inside. ref, mut, as reference, with

Enum - Match - Borrow Wrapped Value

match &value_1 { Type::Variant(value) => { ... } ... }
or
match value_1 { Type::Variant(ref value) => { ... } ... }
Borrows the wrapped value inside. ref, as reference

Enum - Match - Mutably Borrow Wrapped Value

match value_1 { Type::Variant(ref match value) => { ... } ... }
Mutably borrows the wrapped value inside. ref, mut, as reference

std::ops::Range ranges, range-only, ranges-only data type, syntax

basics

Range Types

Returns:
RangeInclusive
Rust Docs: std::ops::RangeInclusive std::ops::RangeInclusive, ops::RangeInclusive, RangeInclusive

Range - Details

Integer Range

= start..end_plus_one
= start..=end
Usage:
use std::ops::Range; let range_1: Range<i32> = 0..4;
Type:
Range<type>
Examples: With .. :
use std::ops::Range; let range_1: Range<i32> = 0..4; for value in range_1 { print!("{} ", value); } println!(); // Prints: 0 1 2 3
With ..= :
use std::ops::Range; let range_1: Range<i32> = 0..=3; for value in range_1 { print!("{} ", value); } println!(); // Prints: 0 1 2 3
Rust Docs: std::ops::Range

Integer Range - Reverse

= (start..end_plus_one).rev()
= (start..=end).rev()
Returns a range that counts down from highest to lowest. Start is the lowest value, end is the highest value. Example:
for value in (0..3).rev() { println!("{}", value); } Prints: 2, 1, 0
Example:
for value in (0..=3).rev() { println!("{}", value); } Prints: 3, 2, 1, 0
count down, -1, reverse, negative, .rev()

Integer Range - With Step

= (start..end_plus_one).step_by(step_size)
= (start..=end).step_by(step_size)
Usage:
use std::ops::Range; let range_1: Range<i32> = (0..=10).step_by(2);
Type:
Range<type>
Rust Docs: std::ops::Range range.step_by(), .step_by()

Float Range

= start..end_plus_one
= start..=end
Usage:
use std::ops::Range; let range_1: Range<f32> = 0.0..4.0;
Type:
Range<type>
Creates a range for floating point values. Rust places a restriction on floating ranges... they can NOT be iterated over. This is due to the imprecise nature of floats. Rust Docs: std::ops::Range

= range_1.start

= range_1.end

Struct

A struct is an immutable custom data type that has named fields. Rust Docs: struct structs, struct-only, structs-only, structures, structure-only, structures-only data type

Struct - Basics

Struct Fields:
struct Struct1 { field_1: T1, field_2: T2, field_3: T3 }
Struct Functions and Methods:
impl Struct1 { fn new(field_1, field_2, field_3) -> Self { Struct1 {field_1, field_2, field_3} } fn function_1(param_1: T4, param_2: T5) { ... } fn method_1(&self, param_1: T, ...) { ... } }
Call Function:
Struct1::function_1(param_1, param_2);
Create:
let value_1 = Struct1 { field_1: value, field_2: value, field_3: value }; let value_2 = Struct1::new(field_1, field_2, field_3);
Access:
let field_1 = value_1.field_1; value_1.method_1(param_1, ...);
summary

Struct - Define

Struct - Define

struct Struct1 { field_1: type, field_2: type, field_3: type }
Defines a structure type. Note: No semicolon (;) is required at the end of the definition. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20 }; println!("Point 1: {}, {}", point_1.x, point_1.y); // Prints: "Point 1: 10, 20"
Rust Docs: struct

Struct - Define Constructor

impl Struct1 { fn new() -> Self { ... } }
Implement a new() function. Rust does not support an intrinsic constructor function by default. The idiomatic way to implement a constructor is to implement a new function. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } impl Point { fn new(x: i32, y: i32) -> Self { Point {x, y} } } let point_1 = Point::new(10, 20); println!("Point 1: {}, {}", point_1.x, point_1.y); // Prints: "Point 1: 10, 20"
Rust Docs: struct ::new(), new() impl-only

Struct - Create

= Struct1 { field_1: value, field_2: value, field_3: value }
Creates an instance of the struct. Note the syntax requires {} around the fields and : between field names and values. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20 }; println!("Point 1: {}, {}", point_1.x, point_1.y); // Prints: "Point 1: 10, 20"
Rust Docs: struct instantiate, new

Struct - Create - Short Syntax / Matching Variables

= Struct1 { field_1, field_2, field_3 }
Defines a structure type. When the field name and variable name are the same, use this syntax (field_name) over the longer form (field_name: variable_name). Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let x = 10; let y = 20; let point_1 = Point { x, y }; println!("Point 1: {}, {}", point_1.x, point_1.y); // Prints: "Point 1: 10, 20"
Rust Docs: struct shorthand instantiate, new

Struct - Create - From Other With Updates

= Struct1 { field_1: value, field_1: value, ..other_struct_1 };
Creates a struct using values from a second instance but updates the named fields with new values. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32, z: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20, z: 100 }; let point_2 = Point { x: -10, y: -20, ..point_1 }; println!("Point 2: {}, {}, {}", point_2.x, point_2.y, point_2.z); // Prints: "Point 2: -10, -20, 100"
Rust Docs: struct instantiate, new update syntax

Struct - Properties

Struct - Destructure

let Struct1 {field_1, field_2, ...} = item_1;
Destructures a struct item into separate values. Ownership is transfered to the new variables. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20}; let Point {x, y} = point_1; println!("Point: {}, {}", x, y); // Prints: "Point: 10, 20"
destructuring, get, items, values, fields

Struct - Get Field Value

= struct_1.field_1
let field_1 = struct_1.field_1;
Returns the value of the given field. access

Struct - Operations

Struct - Assign

let struct_1 = Strut1 { field_1: value, field_2: value, field_3: value, };

Struct - Copy

= Struct1 { ..original }
Creates a duplicate of the original structure. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20 }; let point_2 = Point { ..point_1 }; println!("Point 2: {}, {}", point_2.x, point_2.y); // Prints: "Point 2: 10, 20"
clone, duplicate ..

Struct - Copy With Changes

= Struct1 { field_1: value, field_2: value, ..original, }
Creates a copy of the original but updates the fields with different values. The field updatse must come first. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } let point_1 = Point { x: 10, y: 20 }; let point_2 = Point { y = 200, ..point_1 }; println!("Point 2: {}, {}", point_2.x, point_2.y); // Prints: "Point 2: 10, 20"
clone, duplicate, update, updates, modifications, modify ..

Result

Result<Type, Error>
Type:
std::result::Result
Enum Variants:
pub enum Result<T, E> { Ok(T), Err(E), }
Use to return a data or an error from a function. Result is an enum with 2 values: Ok(), Err(). Return a good result with Ok(). Return an error with Err(). Err requires an error object be returned with the error. Rust Docs: std::result::Result Rust Docs: Ok | Err Ok(), Err() results, result-only, results-only, res-only enums types std::result::Result, result::Result, ::result

Result - Basics

Type:
let result_1: Result<T, E> = ...;
Create:
let result_1 = Ok(value_1); let result_2 = Err(error_1);
If Ok:
if let Ok(value) = result_1 { ... = value; }
Match:
match result_1 { Ok(value) => ..., Err(error) => ... }
Function Return:
fn some_function() -> Result<Type, Error> { // Return good result: return Ok(value); // Return error: return Err(error); }
Propagate Error:
fn call_some_function() -> Result<Type, Error> { // Return Error with ? ... = some_function()?; ... }
Rust Docs: std::result::Result

Returns a predetermined value when the result is an error. Otherwise returns the wrapped value. Will panic if the result is an error. Rust Docs: std::result::Result.unwrap_or() unwrap or, substitute, or else result.unwrap_or(), .unwrap_or()

T

Associated Functions and Methods

These are functions and methods associated with a particular data type. Functions apply to the type (similar to class static methods). Methods apply to an instance of a type. associated-, assoc-, ass-, impl, implement struct-only, structs-only

Associated Functions

associated-functions, ass-fn

Associated Function - Define

impl Type { fn function1() -> return_type { ... } }
Defines a function associated with the given type. Example:
struct Point { x: f32, y: f32 } impl Point { fn distance_from_0_0(point: &Point) -> f32 { (point.x.powi(2) + point.y.powi(2)).powf(0.5) } } let point_1 = Point { x: 10.0, y: 20.0}; let distance = Point::distance_from_0_0(&point_1); println!("Point Distance: {}", distance); // Prints: "Point Distance: 22.36068"
impl-only

Associated Function - Define - Return Self

impl Type { fn function1() -> Self { ... } }
The Self type defines the return type as an instance of the type itself. Example:
struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } impl Point { fn new(x: i32, y: i32) -> Self { Point {x, y} } } let point_1 = Point::new(10, 20); println!("Point 1: {}, {}", point_1.x, point_1.y); // Prints: "Point 1: 10, 20"
impl-only

Associative Function - Call

= Type::function1()
Calls the function associated with the type. ::

Associated Methods

Associative methods are associative functions that apply to an instance of a type. associated-method, ass-meth, self, &self

Associated Method - Define

impl Type { fn function1(self) { ... } }
All Variants:
impl Type { fn function1(self) { ... } fn function2(&self) { ... } fn function3(&mut self) { ... } fn function3(Box<self>) { ... } }
Define an associated method by including the parameter self / &self / &mut self. box impl-only

Associative Method - Call

= item1.function1()
Calls the method associated with the item. .

Attributes

Anything in Form:
#[...]
#![...]
An attribute is metadata relating to some module or item. It is used by the compiler. Apply To Module, Item:
#[...]
Apply To Entire Crate:
#![...]
Rust Docs: Attributes #[, ], #[] #![, ], #![] attribute-only, attributes-only

Attribute - Apply To Module Or Item

#[...]
Example:
#[deprecated] fn deprecated_function() { ... }

Attribute - Apply To Entire Crate

#![...]
Example:
#![allow(dead_code)]

Attribute - Reference

Attribute - Config / Conditional Compile

#[cfg(expression)]
Usage:
#[cfg(expression)] statement;
Includes the statement when the expression is true. Otherwise the statement is excluded. Rust Docs: Conditional Compilation property #[cfg], #[cfg()], cfg()

Attribute - Config / cfg - Equals

#[cfg(property = value)]
Usage:
#[cfg(property = value)] statement;
Includes the statement when the property equals the value. Otherwise the statement is excluded. Rust Doc: Conditional compilation has value, =

Attribute - Config / cfg - Equals Any

#[cfg(any(property_1 = value, property_2 = value, ...)]
Usage:
#[cfg(any(property_1 = value, property_2 = value, ...)] statement;
Includes the statement when any of the properties equals their value. Otherwise the statement is excluded. Rust Doc: Conditional compilation any(), has, properties, value, or

Attribute - Config / cfg - Equals All

#[cfg(all(property_1 = value, property_2 = value, ...)]
Usage:
#[cfg(all(property_1 = value, property_2 = value, ...)] statement;
Includes the statement when all properties equal their values. Otherwise the statement is excluded. Rust Doc: Conditional compilation all(), has, properties, values, and

Attribute - Config / cfg - Not Equal To

#[cfg(not(property_1 = value)]
Usage:
#[cfg(not(property_1 = value)] statement;
#[cfg(not(expression)] statement;
Includes the statement when the property does not equal the value. Otherwise the statement is excluded. Rust Doc: Conditional compilation all(), properties, value, does not, isn't

Attribute - Derive

Tells the compiler to generate default implementations for various features. Rust Docs: Derive derive-only

Attribute - Derive Summary

Clone #[derive(Clone)]
Copy#[derive(Copy)]
Debug#[derive(Debug)]
Default#[derive(Default)]
Hash#[derive(Hash)]
Eq#[derive(Eq)]
Ord#[derive(Ord)]
PartialEq#[derive(PartialEq)]
PartialOrd#[derive(PartialOrd)]
basics

Attribute - Derive Clone

#[derive(Clone)]
Auto implements the Clone trait. Example:
#[derive(Clone)] struct Point { x: i32, y: i32 } fn main() { let point = Point {x: 3, y: 4}; let point_2 = point.clone(); println!("Point: {},{}", &point_2.x, &point_2.y); } // Prints: Point: 3,4
Rust Docs: std::clone::Clone (derive macro) | Clone (trait) #[derive(clone)], (clone), clone #[derive(copy)], (copy), copy std::clone::Clone

Attribute - Derive Copy

#[derive(Copy)]
Tells the compiler give a type 'copy semantics' instead of 'move semantics'. Rust Docs: std::copy::Copy (derive macro) | Copy (trait) #[derive(copy)], (copy), copy std::copy::Copy

Attribute - Derive Debug

#[derive(Debug)]
Auto implements the Debug trait. Provides an implementation for "{:?}" as used by println!(), format!(), etc.. Rust Docs: std::fmt::Debug (derive macro) | Debug (trait) #[derive(Debug)], (debug), debug :?, {:?}

Attribute - Derive Default

#[derive(Default)]
Auto implements the Default trait. This will create a default instance with reasonable initial values. Example:
#[derive(Default)] struct Item { name: String, values: Vec<String>, } fn main() { let mut item = Item::default(); println!("Name: {}", item.name); println!("Values: {:?}", item.values); } // Prints: // // Name: // Values: []
#[derive(default)], default, (default)

Attribute - Derive Hash

#[derive(Hash)]
Auto implements the Hash trait. Rust Docs: std::hash::Hash (derive macro) | Hash (trait) #[derive(hash)], (hash), hash std::hash::Hash

Attribute - Derive Eq

#[derive(Eq)]
Implements the Eq trait. Implements == and != for a type. Rust Docs: std::cmp::Eq (derive macro) | Eq (trait) equals, ==, !=, not equal, compare, comparison #[derive(eq)], (eq), eq

Attribute - Derive Ord

#[derive(Ord)]
Implements the Ord trait. Rust Docs: std::cmp::Ord (derive macro) | Ord (trait) compare, comparison #[derive(Ord)], (ord), ord

Attribute - Derive PartialEq

#[derive(PartialEq)]
Implements the PartialEq trait. Rust Docs: std::cmp::PartialEq (derive macro) | PartialEq (trait) partial eq, equals, compare, comparison #[derive(PartialEq)], (partialeq), partialeq

Attribute - Derive PartialOrd

#[derive(PartialOrd)]
Implements the PartialOrd trait Rust Docs: std::cmp::PartialOrd (derive macro) | PartialOrd (trait) partial ord, compare, comparison #[derive(PartialOrd)], (partialord), partialord :?, {:?}

Allows something the linter would normaly report as an error or warning. The allow is applied to a specific item (e.g. a function or constant). ignore #[allow()]

Allows something the linter would normaly report as an error or warning. The allow attribute applies to the entire module or crate. ignore #![allow()]

Error Handling

There are 2 types of errors in Rust:
  • Recoverable
  • Unrecoverable
Exceptions, except-only, exception-only, exceptions-only Errors, error-only, error-handling-only, errors-only

Error - Basics

Recoverable Error:
fn do_something() -> Result<Type, Error> { // Return good result: return Ok(data); // Return error: return Err(error); }
Propagate Recoverable Error:
fn call_do_something() -> Result<Type, Error> { return do_something()?; }
Handle Recoverable Error:
match result { Ok(data) => { ... } Err(error) => { ... } }
Unrecoverable Error:
panic!("Error Message");
summary

Recoverable Error

result<>, ok(), err()

Recoverable Error - Define

fn do_something() -> Result<T, Error> { // Return good result: return Ok(data); // Return error: return Err(error); }
Use Result<T, E> to return errors. Call Ok() define, new, instantiate

Recoverable Error - Propagate Error

function_1()?
Usage:
fn call_do_something() -> Result<T, Error> { do_something()?; ... OK(data) }
Use the question mark operator to propagate the error to the caller. question mark, ? operator

Recoverable Error - Handle Error

match result { Ok(data) => { ... } Err(error) => { ... } }
match err()

Recoverable Error - Return from Main

fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error + 'static>> { ... }
Usage:
use std::error::Error; fn main() -> Result<(), Box<dyn Error + 'static>> { some_function()?; Ok(()) }
Returns an error from main. The error text will be printed to the console. std::error::Error, main()

Unrecoverable Error

Unrecoverable Error - Panic!

panic!("Error Message");
Rust Docs: std::panic! define, new, instantiate, create panic!()

Unrecoverable Error - Show Stack Trace

Set Environment Variable:
RUST_BACKTRACE=1
Set RUST_BACKTRACE to 1 to enable stack traces during panics (dev environment only). rust_backtrace, environment variable, debug

Functions

fn, fns, fn-only, fns-only funcs, func-only, funcs-only fuctions, function-only, functions-only

Function - Basics

Define - No Parameters:
fn name() { ... }
Define - With Parameters:
fn name(param_1: type, param_2: type) { ... }
Return Value (Explicit):
fn name() { return return_value; }
Return Value (Implicit):
fn name() { return_expression }
Return Multiple Values:
fn name() { return (value_1, value_2); // Return as tuple. }
summary

Function - Define

fn name() { ... }
fn name(param_1: type, param_2: type) -> return_type { return return_value; }
Defines a function. Example:
fn square(value: f64) -> f64 { return value }
definition

Function - Arguments

parameters, args, args-only, arguments-only, params, param-only, params-only

Function - Argument - Pass Borrowed

fn function_1(borrowed: &Type) ...
Call:
function_1(&borrowed);
Passes the value as an immutable borrowed value. Passes by reference (pointer). Use & in the argument type and also on the function call parameter. Example:
fn double(value: &i32) -> i32 { value * 2 } let value = 10; println!("{} doubled = {}", value, double(&value));
pass by reference &

Function - Argument - Pass Borrowed, Mutable

fn function_1(borrowed: &mut Type) ...
Call:
function_1(&mut borrowed);
Passes the value as mutable borrowed. pass by reference &, mut, &mut

Function - Argument - Pass Owned

fn function_1(owned: Type) ...
Call:
function_1(owned);
Passes the value as owned.

Function - Argument - Pass Owned, Mutable

fn function_1(mut owned: Type) ...
Call:
function_1(owned);
Passes the value as mutable owned. Can convert an immutable value into a mutable one. mut

Function - Argument - Pass By Value

fn function1(by_value: type) ...
Passes an argument to the function by value. Applies to primitive types only. Example:
fn double(value: i32) -> i32 { value * 2 } let value = 10; println!("{} doubled = {}", value, double(value));
by value, primitive

Function - Return

Function - Return Value (Explicit)

return return_value;
fn name() -> return_type { return return_value; }
Use the keyword return to explicitly return a value. Example:
fn square(x: i32) -> i32 { return x * x; } fn main() { let value = 4; let square = square(value); println!("{} squared is {}.", value, square); }

Function - Return Value (Implicit)

fn name() -> return_type { return_expression }
If the last expression has no semicolon (;), it is the return value. Example:
fn square(x: i32) -> i32 { x * x } fn main() { let value = 4; let square = square(value); println!("{} squared is {}.", value, square); }

Function - Return Multiple Values

return (value_1, value_2, value_3);
Full Form:
fn name() -> (return_type, return_type, return_type) { return (value_1, value_2, ...); }
Call:
let (return_1, return_2, ...) = name(value);
Return multiple values in a tuple. Example:
fn double_and_triple(x: i32) -> (i32, i32) { let double = x * 2; let triple = x * 3; return (double, triple); } fn main() { let value = 4; let (double, triple) = double_and_triple(value); println!("{} doubled and tripled is {}, {}.", value, double, triple); }

Function - Return Nothing

fn name() { ... // Nothing returned. }
Returns unit by default. Example:
use std::any::type_name; fn type_of<T>(_: T) -> &'static str { type_name::<T>() } /// Returns nothing: fn print_square(x: i32) { let squared = x * x; println!("{} squared is {}.", x, squared); } fn main() { let return_value = print_square(2); println!("returned value type is {}.", type_of(return_value)); } // Prints: // // 2 squared is 4. // returned value type is ().
unit, (), exit no value

Function Type

define, reference, fn

Function Type - Basics

A Function:
fn square(value: i32) -> i32 { value * value }
Create Reference:
let square_2: fn(i32) -> i32 = square;
Call:
let squared_value = square_2(4);
reference, summary

Function Type - Define

fn(type) -> return_type
let reference: fn(type) -> return_type = function_1;
Example:
fn square_a_value(value: i32) -> i32 { value * value } let square: fn(i32) -> i32 = square_a_value; let squared_value = square(4); println!("4 squared is {}.", squared_value); // Prints: "4 squared is 16."

Function Type - Define Function Parameter

fn do_something(function_1: fn(type) -> return_type) { ...
Defines a function to be passed into another function. pass, passing

Closure

A closure is a function that 'closes over' the environment it was defined in. It has access to all the variables that are in scope in that environment. functions, closures, anonymous, lambdas closure-only, closures-only

Closure - Create

new, define, ||

Closure - Create With No Arguments

= || ...
let closure_1 = || ...;
Closure with 0 arguments. Example:
let closure_1 = || println!("Closure 1 called."); closure_1();
zero, 0 parameters

Closure - Create With Arguments

= |param_1: type| ...
let closure_1 = |param_1: type| ...;
Closure with one or more arguments. Example:
let closure_1 = |param_1: &str| println!("param_1 = {}", param_1); closure_1("Value 1"); // Prints: param_1 = Value 1
parameters

Closure - Create - Enclosed Variable - Borrow

move || { ... external_variable ... }
Accesses local variables outside the closed function. Example:
let value = 42; let closure_1 = || println!("value = {}", value); closure_1(); // Prints "value = 42"
local scope, referencing, reference, move

Closure - Create - Enclosed Variable - Own

move || { ... }
Takes ownership local variables outside the closed function. Example:
let value = 42; let closure_1 = move || println!("value = {} (owned)", value); closure_1(); // Prints "value = 42 (owned)"
local scope, referencing, reference, ownership, move

Closure - Call

Closure - Call - Version 1

closure_1(params)

Closure - Call - Version 1

(closure_1)(params)

Generics

generics-only, gen-only, <>

Generic Function

fn

Generic Function - Define

fn function_1 <T> (param_1: T) { ... }
fn function_1 <T1, T2, T3> (param_1: T1, param_2: T2, param_3: T3) { ... }
Allows a function to accept a data type that will be defined later by the calling program.

Generic Function - Bounded Type

fn function_1 <T: Trait1> (param_1: T) { ... }
fn function_1 <T: Trait1 + Trait2> (param_1: T) { ... }
fn function_1 <T: Trait1, U: Trait2> (param_1: T) { ... }
Defines a generic type that must implement a trait. constraints, constrain

Generic Function - Bounded, Where

fn function_1 <T> (param_1: T) where T: Trait1 { ... }
fn function_1 <T> (param_1: T) where T: Trait1 + Trait2 { ... }
fn function_1 <T, U> (param_1: T) where T: Trait1, U: Trait2 { ... }
Defines a generic type that must implement a trait. constraints, constrain

Generic Struct

Generics allows a structure to contain a data type that will be defined later by the calling program. The data type is defined at the time the structure is created.

Generic Struct - Basics

struct Struct1<T> { field_1: T }
impl <T> Struct1<T> { fn function1() -> T { ... } fn function2(param1: T) { ... } ... }
let item_1: Struct1<Type> = Struct1 { value }; let value_1: Type = item_1.field_1;
summary

Generic Structure Implementation - Define

impl <T> Struct1<T> { }
impl <T> Struct1<T> { fn function1() -> T { ... } fn function2(param1: T) { ... } ... }
create, new

Generic Structure Implementation - Use

let item_1: Struct1<ActualType> = Struct1 { value };
= item_1.function1() item_1.function2(value);
create, new, instantiate

Generic Trait

Generic Trait - Define

trait Trait1<T> { ... }

Generic Trait - Define, Bounded

trait Trait1<T: Trait2> { ... }
trait Trait1<T: Trait2, U: Trait3> { ... }
Defines a trait that bounds a generic type to a second trait. The generic T must implement trait Trait2. bind, join, requires

Generic Trait - Define, Bounded, Multiple Traits

trait Trait1<T: Trait2 + Trait3 + Trait4> { ... }
Defines a trait that bounds a generic type to several other traits. +, bind, join, requires

Generic Trait - Implement

impl <T> Trait1<T> for SomeType { ... }
for, impl impl-only

Generic Trait - Implement, Bounded

impl <T: Trait2> Trait1<T> for SomeType { ... }
impl <T: Trait2 + Trait3 + Trait4> SomeTrait<T> for SomeType { ... }
impl <T: Trait2, U: Trait3> SomeTrait<T, U> for SomeType { ... }
for, impl impl-only

Generic Trait - Implement Where

impl <T> Trait1<T> for SomeType Where T: Trait2 { ... }
impl <T> Trait1<T> for SomeType Where T: Trait2 { ... }
impl <T, U, ...> Trait1<T> for SomeType Where T: Trait2, U: Trait3, ... { ... }
for, impl, bounded impl-only

Generics Syntax

Generic Function - Equivalent Syntax

Pass:
fn a_function<T: Trait1>(param_1: T) { <v>...<> }
fn a_function<T>(param_1: T) where T: Trait1 { <v>...<> }
fn a_function(param_1 impl Trait1) { <v>...<> }
Pass as Reference:
fn a_function<T: Trait1>(param_1: &T) { <v>...<> }
fn a_function<T>(param_1: &T) where T: Trait1 { <v>...<> }
fn a_function(param_1 &impl Trait1) { <v>...<> }
where, pass, parameter value

Generic Trait - Equivalent Syntax

impl <T: Trait1> OtherTrait for Struct2 { <v>...<> }
impl <T> OtherTrait for Struct2 { where T: Trait1 { <v>...<> }
where, impl impl-only

Lifetimes

Tells rust the lifetime of borrowed variables so it can check they are valid within a given scope. Lifetimes must be explicit in places where the lifetime can not be inferred by the compiler. Rust Docs: Lifetimes lifetime-only, lifetimes-only, 'a, 'b, define

Lifetime Syntax

&'a T &'a mut T T<'a>
'a '_ 'static
Lifetimes annotations must come before type annotations. explicit, 'a, 'b, 'c, &'a, &'b, &'c, mut

Lifetime Types

Anonymous (Place Holder) Lifetime

'_
Usage:
fn function_1(param &'_) ...
Tells the compiler to infer the lifetime. The lifetime must comply with elision rules. '_, inferred

Static Lifetimes

'static
Usage:
Defines the lifetime of the item to the life of the program. Static items are only removed when the program ends. const and static variables are implicitly 'static. Rust Docs: Static Lifetime 'static

Function Lifetimes

annotation

Lifetime - Function

fn function_1<'a> (param_1: &'a Type) -> &'a Type { ... }
Tells Rust what the lifetimes need to be for values entering and leaving the function. A lifetime associated with an argument tells the compiler that the associated data must have the same scope and lifetime. 'a - Defines a lifetime.

Lifetime - Function Multiple Lifetimes

fn function_1<'a, 'b> (param_1: &'a Type1, param_2: &'b Type2) -> &'c Type { ... }
Tells Rust what the lifetimes need to be for values entering and leaving the function. 'a - Defines a lifetime. 'b - Defines a lifetime.

Lifetime - Function Parameter

fn function_1<'a> (param_1: &'a Type) ...

Lifetime - Funciton Parameter With Type Annotation

fn function_1<'a, T> (param_1: &'a T, param_2...) ...
Defines a lifetime annotation along with a type annotation. Lifetime annotations MUST always come before type annotations.

Lifetime - Function Return Type

fn function_1<'a> () -> &'a Type {
value

Struct Lifetimes

Lifetime - Struct

struct Struct1<'a> { field_1: &'a T field_2: &'a T }

Lifetime - Impl

impl <'a> Struct1<'a> { ... }
implement impl-only

Lifetime - Impl Trait

impl <'a> Trait1 for Struct1<'a> { ... }
implement impl-only

Generic Struct Lifetimes

Lifetime - Generic Struct

struct Struct1<'a, T> { field_1: &'a T field_2: &'a T }

Lifetime - Generic Impl

impl <'a, T> Struct1<'a, T> { ... }
implement impl-only

Lifetime - Generic Impl Trait

impl <'a, T> Trait1 for Struct1<'a, T> { ... }
implement impl-only

Trait Lifetimes

Lifetime - Trait

trait Trait1<'a> { fn function_1(&'a self); }

Variable Lifetimes

Lifetime - Variable

value_1: 'a T
let value_1: 'a T = ...;

Lifetime - Mutable Variable

value_1: 'a mut T
let value_1: 'a mut T = ...;

Lifetime - Elision Rules

Use the following rules to determin when to drop lifetime annotations: 3 Rules:
  • Each argument is assigned an individual lifetime.
  • If exactly 1 argument, the return type gets the same lifetime.
  • If &self is an argument, the return type gets the self lifetime
. Rule 1:
fn function_1(param_1: &T, param_2: &T) -> &T // Elided fn function_1<'a, 'b>(param_1: &'a T, param_2: &'b T) -> &'a T // Compiler Expanded
Rule 2:
fn function_1(param_1: &T) -> &T // Elided fn function_1<'a>(param_1: &'a T) -> &'a T // Compiler Expanded
Rule 3:
fn function_1(&self, param_2: &T) -> &T // Elided fn function_1<'a, 'b>(&'a self, param_2: &'b T) -> &'a T // Compiler Expanded
Rust Docs: Lifetime elision

Macros

Macros are a compile time build tool that run inside your code.
  • Run at Compile Time
  • Modify Source Code
Identified with ! custom macro-only, macros-only, macro!, !

Macro - Basics

Define:
macro_rules! macro_1 { () => { ... } ($param_1:expr, $param_2:literal) { ... $param_1 ... } }
Share:
pub(crate) macro_1;
Use:
macro_1!(...)
Rust Docs: macro_rules! macro_rules!, summary

Macro - Create

macro_rules!
macro_rules! macro_1 { () => { ... } ($param_1:expr, $param_2:literal) { ... $param_1 ... } }
Rust Docs: macro_rules! macro_rules!, define

Macro - Use

marcro_1!()
marcro_1!(param_1, param_2, ...)
call

Macro - Public

pub(crate) use macro_1;
Shares a macro inside a library or app. Must be shared using a use statement. Use (crate) when sharing macros. share use, pub(crate)

Macro - Export from Crate

#[macro_export]
Usage:
#[macro_export] macro_rules! macro_1 ...
Exports the macro to external crates / libraries. Exports from the root of the crate. #[macro_export], macro_export

Macro Parameter Types

Macro Parameter - :expr

$expression_1:expr
Any valid Rust expression. expr, expression

Macro Parameter - :ident

$identifier_1:ident
Any valid Rust identifier (variable or function name). ident, identifier

Macro Parameter - :litreal

$literal_1:litreal
A standard literal. ident, identifier

Macro Parameter - :lifetime

$lifetime_1:lifetime
A lifetime. lifetime,

Macro Parameter - :meta

$attribute_1:meta
Usage:
macro_rules! ... { ($attribute_1:meta) { #[$attribute_1] ... } }
An attribute. meta, attribute, derive, #[derive()]

Macro Parameter - :pat

$pattern_1:pat
A pattern used in a match or let statement. pat, pattern

Macro Parameter - :ty

$type_1:ty
A Rust type. Examples: String, &str, u64, usize ty, type

Standard Macros

Panic Macro

panic!("Error Message");
Reports an error, then terminates the application. Use for unrecoverable errors. Caution - should be used very sparingly, if at all. Rust Docs: std::panic! define, new, instantiate, create panic!(), panic!-only

Todo Macro

todo!();
Use in functions where you haven't coded the result. Prevents compiler errors while coding. Will panic at runtime.
fn incomplete_function() { todo!(); }
Rust Docs: std::todo todo!(), todo-only, todo!-only

Unimplemented Macro

unimplemented!("comment");
Use in functions where you haven't coded the result. Prevents compiler errors while coding. Will panic at runtime.
fn incomplete_function() { unimplemented!(); }
Rust Docs: std::unimplemented unimplemented!(), unimplemented-only, unimplemented!-only

Use / Import

import, use, use-only importing, using module, library, crate, modules, mod-

Use

use module::item;
Allows an item from another module to be used within the current module.

Use - Use All

use module::*;
Imports all public items from another module. * - Wild Card. Matches all public items. everything *, ::*

Use - From Crate

use crate::module::item;
Imports an item defined within the current project / library. References the absolute path to that item within the project. crate:: - Signifies from the root of the project. absolute path, root crate::

Use - From Parent

use super::module::item;
use super::*;
Imports an item relative to the parent module. super:: - From the parent. relative super::, super::*

Use - From Self

use self::module::item;
Imports an item relative to the current module. relative self::

Use - With Export

pub use module::item;
Uses and then exports an item from the current module. Allows other modules to use an item relative to this module instead of from the item's original module. pub, public, global

Use - With Export Locally

pub(crate) use module::item;
Allows an item to be used within the current project or library but does not export it to outside projects. pub

Use - With Alias

use module::item as alias;

Traits

Traits defines shared methods and behavior across types. Traits can only access methods defined in the trait itself. Traits can NOT be instantiated directly (instantiate the implementing type instead). trait-only, traits-only, general

Trait - Basics

Define:
trait Trait1 { const CONSTANT_1: usize = 42; fn function_1(); fn function_2() -> Self; fn function_with_default_implementation() { // Implementation here. } fn method(self); fn method(&self); fn method(&mut self); fn method(Box<self>); fn method_with_default_implementation(&self) { // Implementation here. } }
Implement:
imp Trait1 for Type { fn function_1() { // Implementation here. } fn method_1(&self) { // Implementation here. } fn call_type_method(&self) { Type.method() } fn call_trait_method(&self) { Trait1::method_1(self) } fn use_constant() { ... = Self::CONSTANT_1; } }
Call:
Type::function_1(); let instance_1 = Type::new(); instance_1.method_1();
summary

Trait - Create

Trait - Define

trait TraitName { fn function_1(); fn function_2() -> Self; fn method(&self): }
create, new

Trait - Define Constant

trait trait_1 { const CONSTANT_1: Type = value_1; }
Defines a constant that can be used by all types that implement the trait.

Trait - Define Function

trait trait_1 { fn function_1(); fn function_2() -> Self; }
Defines a trait function. A trait function is independent of any trait instance. create, new

Trait - Define Function - Default Implementation

trait trait_1 { fn function_1 () { // Implementation here. } }
Defines a trait function with a default implementation. Reduces repeated work. Reduces the amount of work implementing structures have to. Can be overridden with an implemenation in the struct trait impl itself. create, new

Trait - Define Method

trait trait_1 { fn method_1(self); fn method_2(&self); fn method_3(&mut self); fn method_4(Box<self>); }
Defines a trait method. Borrow:
fn method_1(&self);
Borrow Mutably:
fn method_1(&mut self);
Boxed:
fn method_1(Box<self>);
Take Ownership1:
fn method_1(self);
Trait methods are always associated with an instance of a trait. 1 - The object is destroyed after this call. create, new, self, box

Trait - Define Method - Default Implementation

trait trait_1 { fn method_1(&self) { // Implementation here. } }
Defines a method with a default implementation. Reduces repeated work. Reduces the amount of work implementing structures have to. Can be overridden with an implemenation in the struct trait impl itself. create, new

Trait - Define Supertrait

trait Supertrait1: Trait1 + Trait2 {}
Combines one or more traits into a single trait. Structs that inherit this trait must implement all the indivdiual traits. Rust Docs: Supertraits make, create, define, join, include, combine, add to, +, multiple

Trait - Define Property

You can not define a property on a trait. You may however define a constant.

Trait - Implement

Trait - Struct Implement

impl TraitName for Type1 { fn traitFunction1(...) { ... } }
Implements a trait function for a given type. Functions can be Type functions (call with ::) or instance methods (defined with &self parameter, called with '.'). impl for impl-only

Trait - Struct Implement - Default Method

trait TraitName { fn traitFunction1(...) { // Implement here. ... } }
Implements a default method for a trait. Any struct implementing the trait can use the default method without having to create their own.

Returns the value of a trait defined constant.

Trait - Call Struct Method

Struct1::method_1(self)
Calls method_1() on the struct. These two calls are equivalent. Can be called from any trait implementation for Struct1. Example:

Unsafe

Rust Docs: Chapter 19 - Unsafe unsafe-only

Unsafe - Rules

Allows you to:
  • Dereference a raw pointer
  • Access or modify mutable static variable
  • Access (but not modify) a union field
  • Implement an unsafe trait
  • Call an unsafe function
  • Call an external C function (unsafe by default?)
Used by:
  • Frameworks
  • Special Packages
basics

"{:>length}"
Usage:
= format!("{:>length}", &value)
println!("{:>length}", &value)
Pads a string on the left side. Examples:
println!("'{:>10}'", "12345"); // Prints: ' 12345'
align right, right justify, string pad-left, justify-right, right-justify, align-right, right-align {:>}

Format - Pad on Left With Fill Character

"{:fill>length}"
Usage:
= format!("{:fill>length}", &value)
println!("{:fill>length}", &value)
Pads a string on the left side with a fill character. Examples:
println!("'{:*>10}'", "12345"); // Prints: '*****12345'
align right, right justify, string pad-left, justify-right, right-justify, align-right, right-align {:>}

Format - Pad on Right

"{:length}" "{:<length}"
Usage:
= format!("{:length}", &value)
println!("{:length}", &value)
Pads a string on the right side. Examples:
println!("'{:10}'", "12345"); // Prints: '12345 '
println!("'{:<10}'", "12345"); // Prints: '12345 '
align left, left justify, string pad-right, justify-left, left-justify, left-right, left-align {:<}, {:}

Format - Pad on Right With Fill Character

"{:fill<length}"
Usage:
= format!("{:fill<length}", &value)
println!("{:fill<length}", &value)
Pads a string on the right side with a fill character. Using a fill character requires the <. Example:
println!("'{:*<10}'", "12345"); // Prints: '12345*****'
align left, left justify, string pad-right, justify-left, left-justify, left-right, left-align {:<}

Format - Escape { }

"{{ ... }}" Usage:
format!("{{ ... }}")
println!("{{ ... }}")
Escape { and } by doubling them up. {{, }}

Format Number - Decimal Places

"{:.decimals}"
Usage:
= format!("{:.decimals}", &value)
println!("{:.decimals}", &value)
Prints the number with the given precision or number of digits after the decimal place. Only works for floating types. Integers will display no decimal places. Example:
println!("'{:.3}'", 3.141592); // Prints: '3.142'
align right, right justify, float, floats, floating values, f32, f64 pad-left, justify-right, right-justify, align-right, right-align {:.}

Format Number - Pad Leading Zeros

"{:0length}"
Usage:
= format!("{:0length}", &value)
println!("{:0length}", &value)
Pads a number with leading zeros. Total length will be at least the length given. Examples:
println!("{:05}", 42); // Prints: 00042
align right, right justify, integers, floats, floating values, f32, f64, 0s pad-left, justify-right, right-justify, align-right, right-align {:0}

Format Number - Pad Leading Zeros, and Decimal Places

"{:0length.decimals}"
Usage:
= format!("{:0length.decimals}}", &value)
println!("{:0length.decimals}}", &value)
Pads a number with leading zeros and displays the given number of digits after the decimal place. Example:
println!("{:08.3}", 3.141592); // Prints: 0003.142
align right, right justify, integer, 0s, floats, floating values, f32, f64 pad-left, justify-right, right-justify, align-right, right-align {:0}, {:.}, {:.}

Format Number - Comma Separated

Can't do directly in Rust. Use a 3rd party library like num-format

Format Number - To Binary

Format:
"{:b}" "{:08b}"
Usage:
= format!("{:b}", &value)
println!("{:b}", &value)
Prints the binary form of a value. Examples:
println!("{:b}", 11); // 1011 println!("{:08b}", 11); // 00001011 println!("{:016b}", 11); // 0000000000001011
let value = 11; let binary = format!("{:b}", value); println!("{} decimal = {} binary.", &value, &binary); // Prints: 11 decimal = 1011 binary.
integer, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128 u8, u16, u32, u64, fu128, usize convert, conversion :b, :08b, {:b}, {:08b}

Format Number - To Binary With Leading 0b

Format:
"{:#b}" "{:#08b}"
Usage:
= format!("{:#b}", &value)
println!("{:#b}", &value)
Prints the binary form of a value with leading '0b'. Examples:
println!("{:#b}", 11); // 0b1011 println!("{:#08b}", 11); // 0b00001011
let value = 11; let binary = format!("{:#b}", value); println!("{} decimal = {} binary.", &value, &binary); // Prints: 11 decimal = 0b1011 binary.
integer, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128 u8, u16, u32, u64, fu128, usize convert, conversion, :b, :#b, {:b}, {:#b}

Format Number - To Hexadecimal (Lower Case)

Format:
"{:x}" "{:02x}" "{:04x}"
Usage:
= format!("{:x}", &value)
println!("{:x}", &value)
Prints the lower case hexadecimal form of a value. Examples:
println!("{:x}", 42); // 2a println!("{:02x}", 42); // 2a println!("{:04x}", 42); // 002a
let value = 42; let hex = format!("{:04x}", value); println!("{} decimal = {} hex.", &value, &hex); // Prints: 42 decimal = 002a hex.
integer, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128 u8, u16, u32, u64, fu128, usize {:x}, :x, {:02x}, :02x, {:04x}, :04x convert, conversion, value

Format Number - To Hexadecimal (Upper Case)

Format:
"{:X}" "{:02X}" "{:04X}"
Usage:
= format!("{:X}", &value)
println!("{:X}", &value)
Returns the upper case hexadecimal form of a value. Examples:
println!("{:X}", 42); // 2A println!("{:02X}", 42); // 2A println!("{:04X}", 42); // 002A
let value = 42; let hex = format!("{:04X}", value); println!("{} decimal = {} hex.", &value, &hex); // Prints: 42 decimal = 002A hex.
integer, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128 u8, u16, u32, u64, fu128, usize {:x}, :x, {:02x}, :02x, {:04x}, :04x convert, conversion, value

Format Number - To Hexadecimal With Leading 0x

Format:
"{:#x}" "{:#04x}" "{:#06x}"
Usage:
= format!("{:#04x}", &value)
println!("{:#04x}", &value)
Returns the hexadecimal form of a value with a leading '0x'. Note: The padding length refers to the total length of the returned string.
format!("{:#04x}", 42) returns "0xa2".
Examples:
println!("{:#x}", 42); // 0x2a println!("{:#02x}", 42); // 0x2a println!("{:#04x}", 42); // 0x2a println!("{:#06x}", 42); // 0x002a
let value = 42; let hex = format!("{:#06x}", value); println!("{} decimal = {} hex.", &value, &hex); // Prints: 42 decimal = 0x002a hex.
integer, i8, i16, i32, i64, i128 u8, u16, u32, u64, fu128, usize convert, conversion, hash, value value {:x}, :x, {:02x}, :02x, {:04x}, :04x, {:06x}, :06x {:#x}, :#x, {:#02x}, :#02x, {:#04x}, :04x, {:#06x}, :06x

write() vs write_all()

fs::write():
  • Calls: File::open(), file.write_all()
file.write():
  • Writes Bytes To The File
  • Returns The Number Of Bytes Written
  • Will Attempt To Write All Bytes
  • Not An Error If Not All Bytes Are Written
file.write_all():
  • Writes All Bytes To The File
  • Returns Nothing
  • Internally Calls write() Until All Bytes Written
Rust Docs: std::fs::write Rust Docs: std::fs::File.write() Rust Docs: std::fs::File.write_all() versus file.write(), .write(), file.write_all(), .write_all() std::fs::file

BufReader - Basics

Read:
use std::fs::File; use std::io::BufReader; use std::io::Read; // Open: let file = File::open(path)?; let mut reader = BufReader::new(file); let mut buffer = [0_u8; max_size]; // Read: loop { let size = match reader.read(&mut buffer) { Err(error) => return Err(error), Ok(0) => break, // EOF Ok(size) => size, }; let content = &buffer[..size]; ... }

BTreeMap - Get Range

= btree_map_1.range(range)
= btree_map_1.range((min_condition, max_condition))
Usage:

use std::ops::Bound::Excluded; = btree_map_1.range((Excluded(min), Excluded(max))
Returns:
Range<Key, Value>
Returns a subset of a BTreeMap. Use the Bound enum to define min and max values and whether they are inclusive or exclusive. Example:
use std::collections::BTreeMap; use std::ops::Bound::Included; let mut items: BTreeMap<String, String> = BTreeMap::new(); items.insert("alpha".to_string(), "Î±".to_string()); items.insert("beta".to_string(), "Î²".to_string()); items.insert("chi".to_string(), "Ï‡".to_string()); items.insert("delta".to_string(), "Î´".to_string()); items.insert("epsilon".to_string(), "Îµ".to_string()); let range = items.range( (Included("beta".to_string()), Included("delta".to_string()))); while let Some((key, value)) = range.next() { println!("{} ({})", value, key); } // Prints: // // Î² (beta) // Ï‡ (chi) // Î´ (delta)
Rust Docs: std::collections::BTreeMap.range() Rust Docs: std::collections::btree_map::Range Rust Docs: std::ops::Bound within, between, subset btreemap.range(), .range() std::collections::btree_map::Range, collections::btree_map::Range, btree_map::Range std::ops::Bound, std::ops::Bound::Included, Bound::included, included, std::ops::Bound::excluded, Bound::excluded, excluded

HashMap

std::collections::HashMap
A collection of key values stored on the heap. Types Must Implement:
Eq + Hash traits
Rust Docs: std::collections::HashMap hashmap-only, hashmaps-only, hashmaps std::collections::HashMap, collections::HashMap, ::HashMap

HashMap - Basics

Create:
let mut map_1 = HashMap::new(); map_1.insert("a", 1); map_1.insert("b", 2); map_1.insert("c", 3);
Access:
let value = map_1.get("b"); match value { Some(value) => println!("Value for 'b': {}", value), None => println!("Key 'b' not found"), }
Update:
map_1.insert("b", 22);
Iterate:
for (key, value) in &map { println!("{}: {}", key, value); }
Remove:
map_1.remove("a");
Exists:
= map_1.contains_key("c")
Properties:
let length = map.len()); let is_empty = map.is_empty());
Clear:
map_1.clear();

define, new, instantiate

HashMap<Key, Value>
Creates an instance of HashMap. Example:
use std::collections::HashMap; let mut hashmap_1 = HashMap::new(); hashmap_1.insert("one", "Value 1"); hashmap_1.insert("two", "Value 2"); let value = &hashmap_1.get(&"one"); println!("{}", value.unwrap()); // Prints: "Value 1"

HashMap - Create From Array

Creates a HashMap from a list of key value tuples. Rust Docs: std::collections::HashMap.from() hashmap::from(), from()

HashMap - Create using Macro

Rust doesn't have a built in macro to create hashmaps so use this one instead:
macro_rules! hashmap { ( $( $key:expr => $value:expr ),* $(,)? ) => { { let mut map = std::collections::HashMap::new(); $(map.insert($key, $value);)* map } }; }
Usage:
use std::collections::HashMap; let map_1 = hashmap!{ "one" => 1, "two" => 2, "three" => 3 }
hashmap!{}

HashSet - Create From Macro

Rust doesn't have a bulit in macro for creating hashsets. You can use an array and HashSet::from. But if you want an actual macro, here you go:
macro_rules! hashset { ($($value:expr),* $(,)?) => {{ let mut set = HashSet::new(); $(set.insert($value);)* set }}; }
Usage:
use std::collections::HashSet; let set_1 = hashset![1, 2, 3];
hashset!(), hashset![]

Rust Docs: std::collections::VecDeque.new() VecDeque::new() new, define, instantiate

Usage:

VecDeque<type>
