Smart Pointers

Smart Pointers Traits:
Deref Drop
Standard Library Smart Pointers:
Arc<T> Shared ownership, thread-safe
Box<T> Heap allocated
Cell<T> Mutates behind immutable
Cow<T> Efficient pass or clone (as needed)
Mutex<T> Shared access, thread-safe
Rc<T> Shared ownership, single-threaded only
Ref<T> Immutable, returned by RefCell
RefCell<T> Runtime borrow checking, single-threaded only
RefMut<T> Mutable, returned by RefCell
RwLock<T> Shared access, thread-safe
Weak<T>(Arc)Weak Arc reference
Weak<T>(Rc)Weak Rc Reference
Rust Docs: Smart Pointers smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only wrapper-only, wrappers-only, wrap, memory management, summary

Smart Pointer Guide

General:
Allocate On Heap
Box<T>
Efficient Conditional Cloning
Cow<T>
Mutate Behind Immutable
Cell<T>
Single-threaded:
Mutate Shared2
RefCell<T>
Multiple Owners, Immutable
Rc<T>
Multiple Owners, Mutable
Rc<RefCell<T>>
Multithreaded:
Mutate Shared1
Mutex<T>
Mutate Shared2
RwLock<T>
Multiple Owners, Immutable
Arc<T>
Multiple Owners, Mutable1
Arc<Mutex<T>>
Multiple Owners, Mutable2
Arc<RwLock<T>>
1 - Single Reader or Writer 2 - Multiple Readers or Single Writer pointers, summary
Arc<T>
Use when: Multiple threads need to share ownership of data.
  • Thread-safe
  • Shared ownership
  • Uses reference counting
  • Immutable access
Box<T>
Use when: You need to allocate data on the heap for a single owner.
  • Allocates on the heap
  • Returns a pointer to that location
  • Single owner
Cell<T>
Use when: You need to mutate data inside a type without requiring mut.
  • Interior mutability behind immutable variable
  • Underlying type must implement Copy
  • Single-threaded only
  • Zero-cost abstraction
Cow<T>
Use when: You need to decide at runtime whether to use borrowed or owned data.
  • Allows access to either borrowed or owned data
  • Transparent to the end user
  • Clones if needed
  • Underlying type must implement ToOwned
Mutex<T>
Use when: You need to safely access mutable data between threads.
  • Thread-safe mutable access
  • Single borrower or owner
Rc<T>
Use when: You need shared ownership of data in a single-threaded environment.
  • Multiple owners
  • Uses reference counting
  • Immutable access
  • Single-threaded only
Ref<T>
Use when: You need to a temporary immutable reference to the inner data of a RefCell.
  • Immutable
  • Returned by RefCell
  • Enforces runtime borrow rules
RefCell<T>
Use when: You need safe mutable access to data in a single-threaded environment.
  • Runtime borrow checking
  • Bypasses compile-time borrow checks
  • Multiple readers, single writer
  • Single-threaded only
RefMut<T>
Use when: You need to a temporary mutable reference to the inner data of a RefCell.
  • Mutable access
  • Returned by RefCell
  • Enforces runtime borrow rules
RwLock<T>
Use when: You need safe mutable access to data between threads, with multiple readers or one writer.
  • Thread-safe
  • Mutable access
  • Multiple readers, single writer
Weak<T> (Arc)
Use when: You need to avoid circular references in a multi-threaded environment.
  • Non-owning reference to Arc
  • Thread-safe
  • Prevents reference cycles
Weak<T> (Rc)
Use when: You need to avoid circular references in a single-threaded environment.
  • Non-owning reference to Rc
  • Single-threaded only
  • Prevents reference cycles
smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only wrapper-only, wrappers-only, wrap, memory management single-threaded, multi-threaded, multi-threading, multithreaded, multithreading

Arc

Type:
std::sync::Arc<T>
Use:
use std::sync::Arc;
An Arc is a pointer to memory on the heap that can have multiple owners across multiple threads. Use when: Multiple threads need to share ownership of data.
  • Thread-safe
  • Shared ownership
  • Uses reference counting
  • Immutable access
ARC = Atomically Reference Counted Rust Docs: std::sync::Arc arc-only, arc<t> std::sync::arc, sync::arc, ::arc, arc smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only

Arc - Create

= Arc::new(value)
Usage:
use std::sync::Arc; let arc_1: Arc<T> = Arc::new(value);
Creates a new Arc pointer with data placed on the heap. Example:
use std::sync::Arc; let arc_1 = Arc::new(42_i32); println!("{}", arc_1); // Prints: "42"
Rust Docs: std::sync::Arc.new() define, instantiate, new Arc::new(), new()

Arc - Properties

Arc - Get - Borrow (Immutable)

Use as if it were not wrapped in an Arc type. Arc automatically dereferences into the underlying type.

Arc - Get - Access Directly (Nope)

Not possible. You can not access the contained value directly without unwrapping the Arc pointer. This includes dereferencing with *. Options:
  • Clone the Contained Data
  • Unwarp the pointer with try_unwrap()
reference, data, element, value

Arc - Reference Count - Strong

= Arc::strong_count(arc_1);
Returns a count of all the owning arc instances for that arc item. Strong Count = Count of all Owners Rust Docs: std::sync::Arc.strong_count() strong count, instances, existing, current arc::strong_count(), strong_count()

Arc - Reference Count - Weak

= Arc::weak_count(arc_1);
Weak instances are instances of the Weak type and imply a non-owning reference to the Ars's data. Weak = Non-Owning References Rust Docs: std::sync::Arc.weak_count() Rust Docs: std::sync::Weak strong count, instances, existing, current arc::weak_count(), weak_count()

Cow

Type:
std::borrow::Cow
Definition:
pub enum Cow<'a, B> where B: 'a + ToOwned + ?Sized, { Borrowed(&'a B), Owned(<B as ToOwned>::Owned), }
A smart pointer that allows you to work with either borrowed or owned data and then efficiently manages access to that data. The end user can decide whether to borrow or take ownership of that data. Taking ownership will clone borrowed data. Use when: You need to decide at runtime whether to use borrowed or owned data.
  • Allows access to either borrowed or owned data
  • Transparent to the end user
  • Clones if needed
  • Underlying type must implement ToOwned
COW = Clone on Write Use on functions where the data may or may not be modified. If modified, return Cow::Owned(T). Otherwise return Cow::Borrowed(&T). Returned data type must allow clone(). Rust Docs: std::borrow::Cow cow-only, enum smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only std::borrow::cow, borrow::cow, ::cow

Cow - Define

= Cow::Borrowed(value)
Usage:
use std::borrow::Cow; let cow_1 = = Cow::Owned(value)

Creates a Cow of an owned value. This value will be returned for .into_owned(). Rust Docs: std::borrow::Cow

Mutex - Get Read Lock (Blocking)

= mutex_1.lock()
Usage:
if let Some(value) = mutex_1.lock() { ... };
Returns:
LockResult<MutexGuard<T>>
Aquires a lock on the mutex. Blocks the current thread until the lock is available. The value is wrapped in a guard. The compiler handles this transparantly so you treat it just like normal. Will panic if another thread panics while holding the lock. Rust Docs: std::sync::Mutex.lock() Rust Docs: std::sync::MutexGuard mutex.lock(), .lock() aquire

Mutex - Get Read Lock (Non-Blocking)

= mutex_1.try_lock()
Usage:
if let Some(value) = mutex_1.try_lock() { ... };
Returns:
TryLockResult<MutexGuard<T>>
Attempt to aquire a lock on the mutex, returning immediately. The value is wrapped in a guard. The compiler handles this transparantly so you treat it just like normal. Rust Docs: std::sync::Mutex.try_lock() Rust Docs: std::sync::MutexGuard mutex.try_lock(), .try_lock() aquire, try to

Returns:
&<T>

  • Immutable access
  • Single-threaded only

Rc - Properties

Rc - Get - Borrow (Immutable)

= rc_1 Use as if not it were not wrapped in an Rc type. Rc automatically dereferences into the underlying type.

Rc - Get - Access Directly (Nope)

Not possible. You can not access the contained value directly without unwrapping the pointer. This includes trying to dereference with *. Options:
  • Clone the Contained Data
  • Unwrap the pointer with try_unwrap()
reference, data, element, value

Rc - Reference Count - Strong

= Rc::strong_count(rc_1);
Returns a count of all the Rc instances for that Rc item. Strong instances are instances of the Rc Type that point to the contained data. They have ownership of that contained data. Strong = Owning References Rust Docs: std::rc::Rc.strong_count() strong count, instances, existing, current rc::strong_count(), strong_count()

Rc - Reference Count - Weak

= Rc::weak_count(rc_1);
Returns a count of all non-owning weak instances to the rc item. Weak instances are instances of the Weak type and imply a non-owning reference to the Rc's data. Weak = Non-Owning References Rust Docs: std::rc::Rc.weak_count() Rust Docs: std::rc::Weak strong count, instances, existing, current rc::weak_count(), weak_count()

RefCell

Type:
std::cell::RefCell<T>
Tracks and enforces borrows at runtime instead of compile time. Safely allowing the contents to be mutated. Use when: You need safe mutable access to data in a single-threaded environment.
  • Runtime borrow checking
  • Bypasses compile-time borrow checks
  • Multiple readers, single writer
  • Single-threaded Only
Tracks borrows and mutable borrows at runtime. Allows multiple immutable borrows or a single mutable borrow. Should not need to be declared mutable. Not thread safe. Rust Docs: std::cell::RefCell refcell-only, refcell<t> std::cell::refcell, cell::refcell, ::refcell, refcell smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only

RwLock

Type:
std::sync::RwLock<T>
Provides runtime tracking of concurrent reads and writes. Use when: You need safe mutable access to data between threads, with multiple readers or one writer.
  • Thread-safe
  • Mutable access
  • Multiple readers, single writer
This type ensures safe concurrent access to data contained inside. It provides either multiple reader access (shared access), or single writer access (exclusive access). Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLock rwlock-only, rwlock<t> std::sync::rwlock, sync::rwlock, ::rwlock, rwlock smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only

RWLock - Properties

RWLock - Get Mutable

= rwlock_1.get_mut()
Returns:
LockResult<&mut T>
Returns a mutable reference to the contained data. Uses static (compile time) borrow checking to enforce borrow checker rules (the borrow happens on rwlock_1 itself). Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLock.get_mut() rwlock::get_mut(), get_mut()

RWLock - Operations

RwLock - Get Read Lock (Blocking)

= rwlock_1.read()
Usage:
if let Some(value) = rwlock_1.read() { ... };
Returns:
LockResult<RwLockReadGuard<T>>
Aquires a read lock on the RW lock. Blocks the current thread until the lock is available (when all write locks are released). The value is wrapped in a guard. The compiler handles this transparantly so you treat it just like normal. Will panic if another thread panics while holding the lock. Example:
use std::sync::RwLock; let rwlock_1 = RwLock::new(42); match rwlock_1.read() { Err(_) => println!("Error aquiring read lock."),o Ok(value) => println!("value = {}", *value), }; // Prints: value = 42
Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLock.read() Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLockReadGuard rwlock.read(), .read() aquire, read-only, only

RwLock - Get Read Lock (Non-Blocking)

= rwlock_1.try_read()
Usage:
if let Some(value) = rwlock_1.try_read() { ... };
Returns:
TryLockResult<RwLockReadGuard<T>>
Attempt to aquire a read lock on the RW lock, returning immediately. Will return None if there are any write locks. The value is wrapped in a guard. The compiler handles this transparantly so you treat it just like normal. Example:
use std::sync::RwLock; let rwlock_1 = RwLock::new(42); match rwlock_1.try_read() { Err(_) => println!("Error aquiring read lock."), Ok(value) => println!("value = {}", *value), }; // Prints: value = 42
Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLock.try_read() Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLockReadGuard rwlock.try_read(), .try_read() aquire, try to, read-only, only

RwLock - Get Write Lock (Blocking)

= rwlock_1.write()
Usage:
if let Some(value) = rwlock_1.write() { ... };
Returns:
LockResult<RwLockGuard<T>>
Aquires a lock on the rwlock. Blocks the current thread until the lock is available. The value is wrapped in a guard. The compiler handles this transparantly so you treat it just like normal. Will panic if another thread panics while holding the lock. Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLock.write() Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLockGuard rwlock.write(), .write() aquire

RwLock - Get Write Lock (Non-Blocking)

= rwlock_1.try_write()
Usage:
if let Some(value) = rwlock_1.try_write() { ... };
Returns:
TryLockResult<RwLockGuard<T>>
Attempt to aquire a lock on the rwlock, returning immediately. The value is wrapped in a guard. The compiler handles this transparantly so you treat it just like normal. Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLock.try_write() Rust Docs: std::sync::RwLockGuard rwlock.try_write(), .try_write() aquire, try to

Weak (Arc)

Type:
std::sync::Weak
A pointer that contains a non-owning reference to some data. Use when: You need to avoid circular references in a multi-threaded environment.
  • Non-owning reference to Arc
  • Thread-safe
  • Prevents reference cycles
Returned by Arc.downgrade(). Used to prevent reference loops. Allows data to be dropped from memory even though this pointer still references it. Makes no guarantees that the data still being present. Does not count towards ownership. Rust Docs: std::sync::Weak weak-only, non-owing, non-owner std::sync::weak, arc::weak, ::weak, weak smart pointer, smart-only, smart-pointer-only, smart-pointers-only

Error Example - Minimal Implementation

use std::error::Error; use std::fmt; use std::fmt::{Display, Formatter}; #[derive(Debug)] struct CustomError { description: String, } impl Error for CustomError {} impl Display for CustomError { fn fmt(&self, formatter: &mut Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result { write!(formatter, "{}", self.description) } }
Return:
return Err(CustomError{description: description});
This implements a custom error type with one property - description. basic, basics, sample, simple, example, custom, define, create error-only

Error Example - Enum Implementation

use std::error::Error; use std::fmt::Display; use std::fmt::Formatter; use std::fmt::Result as FormatResult; #[derive(Debug)] enum CustomError { NotFound, NotAuthorized, Other(String), } impl Display for CustomError { fn fmt(&self, formatter: &mut Formatter) -> FormatResult { match self { CustomError::NotFound => write!(formatter, "Not found"), CustomError::NotAuthorized => write!(formatter, "Not authorized"), CustomError::Other(message) => write!(formatter, "{}", message), } } } impl Error for CustomError {}
Return:
return Err(CustomError::NotFound;
This implements a custom error type with one property - description, and the new method.. basic, basics, sample, simple, example, custom, define, create error-only

Error Example - Nested Error

use std::error::Error; use std::fmt; use std::fmt::{Display, Formatter}; #[derive(Debug)] struct NestedError { description: String, source: Option<Box<dyn Error>>, } impl NestedError { pub fn new(description: String, source: Option<Box<dyn Error>>) -> Self Self {description, source} } } impl Error for NestedError { fn source(&self) -> Option<&(dyn Error + 'static)> { match &self.source { Some(source) => Some(source.as_ref()), None => None } } } impl Display for NestedError { fn fmt(&self, formatter: &mut Formatter<'_>) -> fmt::Result { write!(formatter, "{}", self.description) } }
Return:
return Err(NestedError::new(description, source));
This implements a custom error that nests another error. basic, basics, sample, simple, example, custom, define, create error-only

impl From<FromType> for ToType { fn from(value: FromType) -> ToType { ... } }
= ToType::from(value)
Defines the conversion from one type into another. Rust Docs: std::convert::From::from() from.from(), .from()

From Trait - Examples

For usize:
struct Data { value: usize } impl From<usize> for Data { fn from(value: usize) -> Self { Data {value} } } fn main() { let data = Data::from(42); println!("Value: {}", data.value); }
For String:
struct Data { value: String } impl<T: ToString> From<T> for Data { fn from(value: T) -> Self { Data { value: value.to_string(), } } } fn main() { let data = Data::from(42); println!("Value: {}", data.value); }
Rust Docs: std::convert::From::from()

Index Trait

Type:
std::ops::Index
Implements indexing on a type (= item[index]). Rust Docs: std::ops::Index Example:
use std::ops::Index; struct Items { values: Vec<String>, } impl Index<usize> for Items { type Output = String; fn index(&self, index: usize) -> &Self::Output { &self.values[index] } } let items = Items{values: vec!["A".into(), "B".into(), "C".into()] }; println!("Item 1: {}", &items[1]); // Prints: B
index-only std::ops::Index, ops::Index, ::Index, []

Index Mut Trait

trait IndexMut<IndexType> { fn index_mut(&mut self, value: IndexValueType); }
Type:
std::ops::IndexMut
Implements mutable indexing on a type (= item[index]). Requires: Index Trait The Index Trait must also be implemented. Rust Docs: std::ops::IndexMut Example:
use std::ops::Index; use std::ops::IndexMut; struct Items { values: Vec<String>, } impl Index<usize> for Items { type Output = String; fn index(&self, index: usize) -> &Self::Output { &self.values[index] } } impl IndexMut<usize> for Items { fn index_mut(&mut self, index: usize) -> &mut Self::Output { &mut self.values[index] } } let mut items = Items{values: vec!["A".into(), "B".into(), "C".into()] }; println!("Item 1: {}", &items[1]); let item1 = &mut items[1]; *item1 = "Z".into(); println!("Item 1: {}", &items[1]); // Prints: B // Prints: Z
indexmut-only, mutable std::ops::IndexMut, ops::IndexMut, ::IndexMut, []

Send Trait

trait Send { }
Type:
std::marker::Send
Defines a type than can be transfered (moved) across threads. This is a marker trait and defines no methods. Fine for:
  • Owned primitives (u32, String)
  • Owned collections (Vec=<T>, HashMap=<K,V>) where T/K/V are Send
  • Most standard types
  • Atomic reference counting (Arc<T>)
Avoid for:
  • Non-atomic reference counting (RC<T>)
  • Raw pointers (*const T, *mut T)
  • Thread-local storage
  • Single-consumer types (mpsc::Receiver)
  • FFI/OS handles
Rust Docs: std::marker::Send std::marker::send, marker::send, ::send send-only

Sized Trait

trait Sized { }
Type:
std::marker::Sized
Defines a type which has a known and constant size at compile time. This is a marker trait and defines no methods. Rust Docs: std::marker::Sized std::marker::sized, marker::sized, ::sized sized-only

Sync Trait

trait Sync { }
Type:
std::marker::Sync
Defines a type than can share a reference safely across threads (&T). This is a marker trait and defines no methods. Fine for:
  • Immutable data (shared reads are safe)
  • Types with internal synchronization (Mutex<T>, AtomicU32)
  • Most primitives (u32, bool)
  • Arc<T> where T: Sync
Avoid for:
  • Non-atomic interior mutability (Cell<T>, RefCell<T>)
  • Non-atomic reference counting (Rc<T>)
  • Raw pointers (*const T, *mut T)
  • Types with unsynchronized mutable state
  • mpsc::Receiver, mpsc::Sender
Rust Docs: std::marker::Sync std::marker::sync, marker::sync, ::sync sync-only

Test Assertions - assert!() vs debug_assert!()

assert!() assert_eq!() assert_ne!() :
  • Is present in development and release versions.
debug_assert!() debug_assert_eq!() debug_assert_ne!() :
  • Is present in development version only.
  • Removed by the compiler in the release version.
  • Use in code to test only in development.
versus assert!(), assert_eq!(), assert_ne!() debug_assert!(), debug_assert_eq!(), debug_assert_ne!()

Test Fixtures

There is no specific language features to setup and teardown test fixtures. Instead, implement your own setup() and teardown() functions and call them from each test method.

Test Fixture - Setup

There is no special built-in Rust features for creating and manage test environments. Instead, define your own and call from your test methods. Define:
fn setup() -> setup_data_type { ... }
Use:
#[test] fn some_test() { let test_data = setup(); ... }

print! - Stay on Line

print!("Print and stay on line.\r");
print!("{}\r", value);
Usage:
use std::io::stdout; use std::io::Write; print!("{}\r", value); let result = stdout().flush();
Prints to the standard out. No newline is sent. Requires the .flush() to submit the print. Using std::io::Write brings in the flush() trait. Example:
use std::io::stdout; for value in (5..=0).rev() { print!("{}\r", value); stdout().flush().unwrap(); } println!(); // Prints: "5", "4", "3", "2", "1", "0"
Rust Docs: std::print standard out, stdout, no newline, macros print, print!(), print-only, print!-only stdio().flush(), .flush()

print! - Flush

= stdout().flush()
Usage:
use std::io::stdout; use std::io::Write; print!("{}\r", value); let result = stdout().flush();
Forces print!() to write its contents to the screen. print!() does not write to the screen immediately. Use flush() to make it happen. standard out, stdout, no newline, macros, force print print, print!(), print-only, print!-only stdio().flush(), .flush()

Feature Gate / Conditional Compilation

conditionals compile

Feature Compile - Basics

Code:
#[cfg(feature = "feature-name")] // Code statement / function / type goes here.
Code (when not using feature):
#[cfg (not(feature = "feature-name"))] // Code statement / function / type goes here.
Cargo.toml:
[features] default = [crate-needed-for-default-only, ...] feature-name = [feature-needed-crate-1, feature-needed-crate-2, ...] feature-with-no-additional-crates = [] [dependency] crate-used-by-all = "1.0" crate-needed-for-default-only = { version = "1.0", optional = true } feature-needed-crate-1 = { version = "1.0", optional = true }
Build:
cargo build --features feature-name
cargo build --features "feature-1, feature-2"

Feature - Code

Feature - Include Code

#[cfg(feature = "feature-name")] // Code statement / function / type goes here.
Includes the code after the #[cfg] attribute when the feature is included. #[cfg]

Feature - Include Code when Any Feature

#[cfg(any(feature = "feature-1", feature = "feature-2"))] // Code statement / function / type goes here.
Includes the code after the #[cfg] attribute when any of the listed features is included. #[cfg], any()

Feature - Include Code when All Features

#[cfg(all(feature = "feature-1", feature = "feature-2"))] // Code statement / function / type goes here.
Includes the code after the #[cfg] attribute when all of the listed features are included. #[cfg], all()

Feature - Exclude Code

#[cfg(not(feature = "feature-name"))] // Code statement / function / type goes here.
Include the code after the #[cfg] attribute if and only if the feature is not present. #[cfg]

Features - Cargo.toml

configuration, [features], crate dependency, dependencies

Feature - Cargo.toml - Define Feature

[features] feature-name = []
Defines an application feature. This feature doesn't require any special crates (empty []).

Feature - Cargo.toml - Define Crates for Feature

[features] feature-name = [feature-needed-crate-1, feature-needed-crate-2, ...] [dependency] feature-needed-crate-1 = { version = "1.0", optional = true } feature-needed-crate-2 = { version = "1.0", optional = true }
Defines the crates needed by the feature. The crates must have the property optional = true. optional = true

Feature - Cargo.toml - Define Crates For Default without Features

[features] default = [non-feature-crate-1, non-feature-crate-2, ...] [dependency] non-feature-crate-1 = { version = "1.0", optional = true } non-feature-crate-2 = { version = "1.0", optional = true }
Defines the crates needed when no feature is present. The crates must have the property optional = true. optional = true, default

Feature - Cargo.toml - Crate For All

[dependency] crate-used-by-all = "1.0"
This crate is included in all builds. Leave out the optional =.

How To

how-to

Command - Execute

cmd!(command param1 param2 ...)
Equivalent To:
let command1 = std::process::Command::new("command"); command.arg("param1"); command.arg("param2");
The cmd! command and parameters do not require quotes around the names (confirm). Rust Docs: std::process::Command cmd!, std::process::Command:

Command Line Arguments - Get

= args().collect()
Full Form:
use std::env::args; let args: Vec<String> = args().collect();
Returns:
Vec<String>
Returns the command line arguments passed to your application. Includes the command name (first entry). Example:
use std::env::args; fn main() { let args: Vec<String> = args().collect(); let command = &args[0]; let first = &args[1]; println!("All: {:?}", args); println!("Command: {}", command); println!("First: {}", first); }
Rust Docs: std::env.args() parameters, params, args std::env::args(), env::args(), args(), args().collect()

Command Line Arguments - Get All Except First (Command Name)

= args().skip(1).collect()
Full Form:
use std::env::args; let args: Vec<String> = args().skip(1).collect();
Returns:
Vec<String>
Returns the command line arguments passed to your application. Rust Docs: std::env.args() parameters, params, args std::env::args(), env::args(), args(), args().collect()

Compile - Small Code

cargo.toml:
[profile.release] codegen-units = 1 lto = true opt-level = "z" panic = "abort" strip = true
Compile:
cargo --release
Commented cargo.toml:
[profile.release] codegen-units = 1 # Minimizes Size By Reducing Parallel Build Processes lto = true # Enable Link Time Optimization opt-level = "z" # Optimize for size panic = "abort" # Prevents stack unwinding, etc. strip = true # Strips symbols
command, cargo, --release

Current Working Directory - Get

= current_dir()
Usage:
use std::env::current_dir; = current_dir()
Returns:
Result<PathBuf>
Returns the current directory. Example:
use std::env::current_dir; use std::path::PathBuf; let path: PathBuf = current_dir().unwrap(); let directory = path.to_str().unwrap(); println!("Current Directory: {}", &directory);
Rust Docs: std::env::current_dir Rust Docs: std::path::PathBuf pwd, cwd, path std::env::current_dir(), env::current_dir(), current_dir()

Function - Curry

= move |...| function_1(a, ...)
Use a closure to curry a function parameter. Example:
fn add(x: isize, y: isize, z: isize) -> isize { x + y + z } let a = 1; let b = 2; let c = 3; let curried = |y, z| add(a, y, z); let total = curried(b, c); println!("{}", total); // Prints: 6
curried, parameter, closure

Index Operations - Implement

To implement index operations, implement Index, and IndexMut traits on these: Range, RangeInclusive, RangeFrom, RangeTo (implement for usize): Implement:
std::ops::Index std::ops::IndexMut
For These:
usize std::ops::Range std::ops::RangeInclusive std::ops::RangeFrom std::ops::RangeTo
Implement these to implement index operations on a type (= item[index], = item[from..to], etc.). Example:
use std::ops::{Index, IndexMut}; use std::ops::{Range, RangeInclusive, RangeFrom, RangeTo}; pub struct Data<V> { items: Vec<V>, } // Index: [index] â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ // impl<V> Index<usize> for Data<V> { type Output = V; fn index(&self, index: usize) -> &Self::Output { &self.items[index] } } impl<V> IndexMut<usize> for Data<V> { fn index_mut(&mut self, index: usize) -> &mut Self::Output { &mut self.items[index] } } // Range: [from..to] â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ // impl<V> Index<Range<usize>> for Data<V> { type Output = [V]; fn index(&self, range: Range<usize>) -> &Self::Output { &self.items[range] } } impl<V> IndexMut<Range<usize>> for Data<V> { fn index_mut(&mut self, range: Range<usize>) -> &mut Self::Output { &mut self.items[range] } } // Range: [from..=to] â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ // impl<V> Index<RangeInclusive<usize>> for Data<V> { type Output = [V]; fn index(&self, range: RangeInclusive<usize>) -> &Self::Output { &self.items[range] } } impl<V> IndexMut<RangeInclusive<usize>> for Data<V> { fn index_mut(&mut self, range: RangeInclusive<usize>) -> &mut Self::Output { &mut self.items[range] } } // Range: [from..] â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ // impl<V> Index<RangeFrom<usize>> for Data<V> { type Output = [V]; fn index(&self, range: RangeFrom<usize>) -> &Self::Output { &self.items[range] } } impl<V> IndexMut<RangeFrom<usize>> for Data<V> { fn index_mut(&mut self, range: RangeFrom<usize>) -> &mut Self::Output { &mut self.items[range] } } // Range: [..to] â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ // impl<V> Index<RangeTo<usize>> for Data<V> { type Output = [V]; fn index(&self, range: RangeTo<usize>) -> &Self::Output { &self.items[range] } } impl<V> IndexMut<RangeTo<usize>> for Data<V> { fn index_mut(&mut self, range: RangeTo<usize>) -> &mut Self::Output { &mut self.items[range] } } // Main â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€â”€ // fn main() { let items = Data {items: vec![1, 2, 3, 4, 5]}; let item = &items[2]; println!("Item: {}", item); for item in &items[1..4] { println!("{}", item); } }
Rust Docs: std::ops::Index | IndexMut Rust Docs: std::ops::Range | RangeInclusive | RangeFrom | RangeTo [], .., ..=, index, range, overload operator

Input - Read from Keyboard

= stdin().read_line(&mut value)
Usage:
use std::io::stdin; let mut value = String::new(); match stdin().read_line(&mut value) { Ok(_) => { value.pop(); // Removes the \n at the end the input. value } Err(error) => { ... } }
Returns:
Result<usize>
Reads from the standard input into value. Returns the number of bytes read. Includes the \n used to complete the input. Rust Docs: std::io::Stdin.read_line() std::io::stdin(), io::stdin(), stdin(), stdin().read_line(), .read_line() stdin, standard in, keyboard

Minimalist Application

#![no_std] #![no_main] extern crate libc; #[no_mangle] pub extern "c" fn main() -> isize { 0 } #[panic_handler] fn my_panic(_info: &core::panic::PanicInfo) -> ! { loop{} }
Creates the smallest code possible. Use Small Code compiler options. small, smallest, tiny #![no_std], no_std, #![no_main], no_main

Pass String or &str

<IntoString: Into<String>>
Usage:
fn some_function<IntoString: Into<String>>(string_1: IntoString) { = string_1.into() }
Use the Into trait when you need to pass either String or &str. Call .into() to convert to an actual String. Example:
fn print_string<IntoString: Into<String>>(string_1: IntoString) { let actual = string_1.into(); println!("{}", &actual); } print_string("As &str"); print_string(String::from("As String")); // Prints: // // As &str // As String
either or, passing, into, parameter, IntoString Into<String>

String - Return &str or String

Cow<'a, str>
fn <'a>function_1(...) -> Cow<'a, str> { ... }
Use Cow to return either a str or String from a function. Example:
use std::borrow::Cow; fn dot_dot_dot<'a>(text: &'a str) -> Cow<'a, str> { if text.chars().count() <= 5 { Cow::Borrowed(text) } else { let start: String = text.chars().take(10).collect(); Cow::Owned([start, "..."].concat()) } } println!("{}", dot_dot_dot("12345")); println!("{}", dot_dot_dot("1234567890")); // Prints: // // 12345 // 12345...
cow, cow-only, patterns

Variable - Replace Value

use std::mem::replace; = replace(destination, replacement_value)
Replaces a value with a new value. Returns the original value. Uses: Move a value out of a mutable reference, especially behind a complex structure. Update a value inside a mutable variable without violating the borrow checker. Rust Docs: std::mem::replace() update std::mem::replace(), mem::replace(), ::replace(), replace()

Swaps the values of two variables while keeping mutability. The variables must be of the same type. Rust Docs: std::mem::swap() update std::mem::swap(), mem::swap(), ::swap(), swap()

Reference - Symbols

Official Rust Docs: Operator Appendix symbols-only, symbol-only, sym-only

Symbol _

Identifies an intentionally unused variable.
let _unused_variable = 0;
leading underscore

Symbol ?

Question Mark Operator (Error Propagation Operator). Propagates a Result::Err error to the parent function.
fn function_1 -> Result<T, E> { function_2()?; }
question mark, propagation, error

Symbol ;

Command Terminator
println!("This is terminated by a semicolon");
semicolon

Symbol ;

Array Type Size Separator
let array_1: [T; size] = ...;
semicolon, [;]

Symbol .

Dot Operator The dot operator identifies the next item as an instance field or method. dot operator

Symbol ..

Iterator Returns values starting with the minimum value to up to the value before the end value.
= start..end_plus_one
dot operator

Symbol ..

Struct Copy Operator Creates a copy of a struct item.
= Struct1 { ..item1 }
dot operator, struct

Symbol ..=

Iterator Returns values starting with the starting value to up to and including the end value.
= start..=end
dot operator

Symbol :

Type Definition
let value: Type;

Symbol :

Generic Type Bound Bounds the trait and lifetime of a type.

fn function_1<T: 'a> () {}

Symbol :

Structure Field Assignment
let value = Struct1 { field: value };

Namespace Path Separator
std::vec::Vec
double colon

Symbol ::

Symbol ::*

Import all public items from the module.
used library::module::*
double colon

Symbol ::<>

Type Annotation / Turbofish. Tells the compiler what type should be returned from a function with a generic parameter.
::<Type>
= item.into::<ConcreteType>()
Here ConcreteType tells the compiler what type should be returned from the function .into(). ::<>, turbofish

Symbol dyn

Defines a dynamically dispatched trait.

Memory

  • Data Memory
  • Stack Memory
  • Heap Memory

Memory - Data Memory

Used for data that is both static and fixed in size data. Static - Data that is alive for the entire life of the application. Example: String

Memory - Stack Memory

Stores function variables. Memory locations wouldn't change for the life of the function call. The compiler optimizes this memory very efficiently.

Memory - Heap Memory

For dynamically allocated memory, memory that may need to be moved, resized, added, deleted, etc. This is the slowest and relatively most costly memory to use.

Heap Memory - Allocation

Allocating new data to the heap memory.

Heap Memory - Deallocation

Removing existing data from the heap memory.

Heap Memory - Speed / Performance

Heap memory is slower than stack memory when allocating, accessing and deallocating that memory. Allocation takes time as Rust must find a space that is free and big enough to fit the allocation request. Accessing takes a little longer than stack memory access as there is always a pointer call first. Deallocation takes time because allocation tables need to be updated.

Memory - Where Is My Data Stored?

str:
  • Stack
  • Heap
  • Application Binary
Primitives: Structs with Primitives Only:
  • Stack
  • (by default unless explicitly put on heap)
Size Known Only at Runtime (e.g. String, Vec): Explicitly Placed on Heap (e.g. Box)
  • Heap
  • (always dynamically allocated)

Reference - Rust Conventions

Prelude Module

Expose commonly accessed functions, types, and traits from a single place.
use module::prelude::*;
Use a prelude module to expose commonly accessed functions, types, and traits from one single module. These items can be defined elsewhere but are exposed collectively here (pub use T;). Consumers will then only need to import the prelude module to gain access to them. Use prelude inside your app to allow internal modules to access most commonly used items. This will make it easy for other modules to access those items. For a library, expose the most commonly used or needed items here. Including required items in one place will help consumers of the library work more effectively. Tip: Less is more. Don't overload your prelude file. Example: /src/prelude.rs:
pub use crate::types::ImportantType pub use crate::traits::ImportantTrait
prelude, ::prelude::*;, prelude::*, prelude.rs

Reference - Coming From Other Languages

++, -- Operators

Not supported in Rust. Use Instead:
a += 1; a -= 1;
increment, decrement

Classes

Rust does not support classes. Use structures and traits instead.

Class Constructors

Rust does not support constructors. Implement a static function instead. new() is typically used (by convention). Example:
pub struct Item { pub id: usize, pub name: String } impl Item { pub fn new(id: usize, name: &str) { Item { id, name: name.to_string() } } }

Dictionary, Map, Table

Use: HashMap dict, dicts, maps, associative arrays, hash table

Dictionary, Map, Table - Ordered

Use: BtreeMap dict, dicts, maps, ordered, sorted, associative arrays

Functions - Variadic

Not supported in Rust Variadic: Functions that take a variable number of parameters.

Inheritance

Rust does not support inheritance or any form of object oriented programming. Use traits instead.

Interfaces

Rust uses traits which are similar to interfaces. Use traits.

List

Use: Array (immutable sequence), Vec (mutable sequence) lists

Object Oriented Programming (OOP)

Rust does not supported in Rust. Use structures and traits instead.

Null

Null is not supported directly in the language and there is no Null type. Use: Option nulls type

Set

Use: HashSet sets

Set - Ordered

Use: BTreeSet sets, ordered, sorted

Stack

Use: Vec
let vec_1: Vec<V> = Vec::new(); vec_1.push(value); last = vec_1.pop(); size = vec_1.len();
stacks, stack-only, stacks-only

Switch, Case Statement

For switch or case statement use match statement. Use: Match

Tree

Use: BTreeMap or BTreeSet trees tree-only, trees-only

Rust Patterns

pattern-only, patterns-only

Pattern - Enum Match Guard

let value = match enum_1 { GuardVariant => return ...; NeededVariant(value) => value, }
or
let value = match enum_1 { NeededVariant(value) => value, _ => return ...; }
Assigns the needed value or returns immediately for other types. The guard returns immediately when a non needed value or guard value is encountered. Why? Keeps the remaining code much simpler (no nests of match / if statements). assign

Pattern - NewType

pub struct NewType1(WrappedType);
Defines a new type by wrapping an existing type. This is a zero cost abstraction. Why? Adds clarity to the type. Example:
pub struct Seconds(i64); seconds = Seconds(60); println("{}", seconds.0) // Prints: 60
new type, wraps type, external trait, wrapper newtype-only

Pattern - NewType - External Trait and Type

pub struct NewType1(ExternalType); impl ExternalTrait for NewType1 { ... }
Implements a trait for an external trait and type. Why? Allows you to add a trait to a type when both are external to your code. new type, wraps type, external trait, wrapper newtype-only

Whats the Difference

vs, versus

Array vs Slice

Array:
  • Fixed Size
  • Stores Data Directly
Slice:
  • A View into an Array or Sliceable Data Type
  • Assigned Dynamically
  • Size Assigned by App as Needed

Copy vs Clone Traits

Copy:
  • Does a bitwise copy of a type's data.
  • Implements "copy semantics" (automatic copy on assignment).
Clone:
  • Provides an explicit clone function to copy the type.
  • Copies are made explicitly only (.clone())

From vs Into Traits

Prefer From. Both:
  • Define how to convert one type into another.
  • Both are non failing (must complete successfully).
From:
  • Prefer From over Into.
  • Is implemented on the target type (to type).
Into:
  • Is implemented on the source type (from type).
  • Often requires type annotations (turbofish) to work
  • ... because the inference engine has difficulty determining the target type.
Traits

Function vs Method

Function:
  • A standalone function.
  • Called directly.
  • function_1()
Associated Function:
  • A function associated with a type.
  • Defined in an impl clause.
  • Referenced through the type name.
  • Referenced with "::"
  • Type::function_1()
Method:
  • A function associated with an instance of a type
  • Defined in an impl clause and starts with the self parameter.
  • Referenced from the instance variable.
  • Referenced with "."
  • item_1.method_1()
associated

Eq vs PartialEq Traits

Eq:
  • Use when x == x is always true.
  • Requires full equivalence (reflexive property is true).
  • Required by HashSet, HashMap
PartialEq:
  • Use when x == x may not always true.
  • Example - NaN != Nan
  • Implements partial equivalence only (reflexive property is not true).
  • NOT usable in HashSet, HashMap
traits

iter() vs iter_mut() vs into_iter()

All iterate over a collections elements. iter():
  • Borrows the elements.
  • Returns &T.
iter_mut():
  • Mutably borrows the elements.
  • Returns &mut T.
into_iter():
  • Takes ownership of the collection elements.
  • Returns T.
.iter(), .into_iter()

Iterator vs IntoIterator Traits

Iterator:
  • Iterates over a sequence of values.
IntoIterator:
  • Returns an iterator.

todo!() vs unimplemented!()

Both will panic when executed. Use todo!() for future features. Use unimplemented!() for things that must be implemented now. macros

Terms

glossary, definition, term-only, terms-only

Algebraic Data Type (ADT)

A kind of composite type. Contains 2 types: Sum Type Product Type

Algebraic Data Types - Product Type

An item contains one or more items. A has a B and a C (contains fields). Rust implements product types using structs.

Algebraic Data Types - Sum Type

An item is a variation of something. It is one of a limited set. A is a B or A is a C (variants). Rust implements sum types using enums.

Arena Tree / Index-based Tree

A tree that references elements by their indices instead of direct pointers. Stores data in a contiguous block of memory (such as a vec). The tree then stores the index location of the elements, instead of pointers. This avoids mutable reference or lifetime issues caused by the borrow checker. Also Called: Index-based Tree arena-based, index-based

Attribute

Metadata that relates to some crate, module or item. It is used by the compiler.

Borrow Checker

A component of the compiler that tracks lifetime and borrowing of a resource. It ensures the borrows are valid and end before the owner is destroyed.

Cargo

Rust's build system and package manager.

Clippy

Rust's included code linter. lint, linter

Copy Semantics

The automatic duplication of an object's value when the object is assigned or passed. Primitive types implement copy semantics by default. Other types must implement the Copy trait to use copy semantics. vs "Move Semantics"

Crate

A compiled unit of a program. A library that can be pulled into a project. Includes a list of dependencies.

Count - Strong Count

A count of owners of an ARC or RC pointer. Allows shared ownership of a resource. The resource is deleted when count = 0. Will delete even if the weak count is > 0. VS: Weak Count

Count - Weak Count

A count of non-owning instances of an ARC or RC pointer. Used where you need to have more than one reference to a resource (e.g. doubly linked list, or anything with circular references). Must check when using the resource to see it still exists. Can be upgradet to a strong pointer if needed. VS: Strong Count

Destructor

An object's destructor releases any owned resources, freeing up memory. Rust automatically calls an objects destructor when the object goes out of scope. Rust calls the Drop trait to execute the destructor. drop

Divergent Expression

An expression that exits out of the current block to somewhere else. Think return or panic!(). divergence

Dynamic Dispatch

Where Rust determines the trait functions to call dynamically at runtime. Used when the trait is known but not the actual type until runtime. Rust implements a vtable lookup to find the correct function to call.
&dyn Trait1 Box<dyn Trait1>
dynamically dispatched

Dynamically Sized Type (DST)

Also Called: Unsized Type unsized type

Lifetime Elision

The ommiting of lifetime annotations for parameters where the compiler can infer the lifetime. Compiler infers omitted lifetime annotations using these rules:
  • Each &param gets unique lifetime
  • Single parameter -> return inherits its lifetime
  • &self -> return inherits self's lifetime
Parameters must be annotated explicitly if there is any ambiguity. elide

Epoch

The time at Unix Time 0. January 1st, 1970 at 00:00:00 UTC. unix time

Epoch Time / Unix Time

The time that has passed in seconds since the Unix epoch (January 1st, 1970).

Expression

Something that evaluates to a value.

Fat Pointer

A fat pointer is structure containing a pointer and some metadata. The internal pointer stores the data's location. The metadata describes that data. It can be used to track an instance that implements a trait of some kind but the actual instance isn't known until runtime. Example - &str: This fat pointer contains a pointer to a string (the pointer) and the length of that string (the metadata). Example - &dyn Trait1: Consists of 2 internal pointers, one pointing to the implementing structure data (the pointer), the other pointing to the vtable for the Trait methods (the metadata).

Ferris

The unofficial mascot of Rust mascot

Foreign Function Interface (FFI)

This is Rust's interface to other programming languages and vice versa. It is based on C's ABI (Application Binary Interface)

Function Overloading

Not supported in Rust. Use traits instead.

Graydon Hoare

The creator of Rust. Graydon created Rust at Mozilla in 2006. rust creator

Gorilla

Here is a gorilla ğŸ¦

Higher Order Functions (HOF)

These do either or both:
  • Take One or More Functions as Parameters
  • Return a Functions

Hoisting

The moving of variables, constants and functions to the top of the containing scope. Rust hoists constants. Constants will always be declared before any other code runs no matter where they are actually defined. constants

Implicit Casting

Not supported in Rust. Always explicitly cast your variables.

Interior Mutability

The ability to mutate internal data especially when you have an immutable reference to it. This is important when Rust's borrow checker would ordinarily disallow it. Use these types:
Cell<T> RefCell<T> Mutex<T> RwLock<T>

Low Level Virtual Machine (LLVM)

A language independent compiler that translates code into machine code using an intermediate representation. Supports a wide range of platforms and architectures. Used by Rust to compile code into executable binaries. Wikipedia: LLVM

Marker Trait

A marker trait is a trait that is used to identify a property of a type. Marker traits do not have any methods associated with them and therefore do not requiry any method implementation.

Method - Instance Method

This is a method associated with an instance of a type and is accessed with the . operator.

Method - Static Method

This is a method associated with a type and is accessed with the :: operator.

Method Overloading

Not supported in Rust. Use traits instead.

Module

A group of functions and types within a crate.

Move Semantics

The transfer of an object's ownership when the object is assigned or passed. vs "Copy Semantics"

Multi-Producer Single-Consumer (MPSC)

A first in first out (FIFO) queue used to communicate between threads.

Panic

An unrecoverable error.

Pinning

Pinning prevents a value from being moved from it's current memory location. Used in async/await code. pinned

Pointer

A variable that points to a location on the memory heap. Pointers store memory addresses. Pointers themselves are stored in the stack. The most common pointer in Rust is the reference (&)
*pointer

Primitive

A data type built into the language.

Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII)

This simply means the constructor acquires a resource, the destructor releases it. Rust enforces this. So when a resource goes out of scope, it's destructor is called and the resource is released. (yes, RAII is a terrible name)

Rust Library (RLIB)

The intermediate compiled libraries created by Rust.

Rustacean

Someone who likes and uses Rust.

RustC

Rust's compiler.

RustFMT

Rust's included code formatting tool. formatter, fmt

Rustic

Code that is idiomatic Rust. There isn't an official term for idiomatic Rust but I'd love if this became it! idiomatic rust

Rustup

Rust's included installer and Rust version switcher. https://rustup.rs

Smart Pointer

A structure that acts like a pointer but has extra functionality (typically relating to memory management). Smart pointers implement traits:
Deref Drop
Most Common Standard Library Smart Pointers:
Arc<T> Box<T> Cell<T> Cow<T> Rc<T> Ref<T> RefMut<T> RefCell<T> RwLock<T> Weak<T>

String Slice

The name for the &str data type.

Statement

A command that performs some action but does not return a value. This is usually in aid of evaluating an expression.

Threads - Green Threads

A thread that runs concurrently (not true parallel) and is controlled by program. Multiple green threads will run concurrently on a single native thread. Rust supports this through 3rd party libraries.

Threads - Native / OS Thread

A thread that runs in parallel and is controlled by the operating system. Core Rust only supports native threads.

Trait - Orphan Rule

You can only implement a trait when either the trait or the type is defined locally in the current crate. This rule ensures type safety across different crates by preventing conflicting implementations. implementing across modules

Transmute

An unsafe function that reintreprets the underlying bit value of a type as another type.

Type Annotation / Turbofish

Used to explitly define generic type returned from a call where the inferencing engine can't automatically determine it.
::<>
= item.into::<String>()
In cases where type inferencing is needed to determine the type (eg into() or collect()), the compiler needs to know which type to convert to. To solve this problem, you annotate the function name with the return type. Also called: Turbofish ::<>, fish

Type - Saturated Type

A type that returns the maximum value when an operation causes the original value to overflow.

Type - Wrapped Type

A type that returns the minimum value when an operation causes the original value to overflow.

Unit

An empty tuple. These are returned by functions that do not return any value.

vtable

Defines details for a type instance that implements a trait but the actual type isn't known until runtime. Referenced from a fat pointer (&dyn Trait1). Each trait defines a separate vtable.

WebAssembly (WASM)

Portable binary-cod that runs in a web browser. Rust supports compiling to WebAssembly. Wikipedia: WebAssembly

Zero Cost Abstraction

These absractions give you high-level language features (such as safety and expressiveness) without sacrificing performance.
